WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:01.980
Okay. Good afternoon, everybody.

2
00:00:02.100 --> 00:00:05.840
Welcome to the 2026 AACR meeting. I hope

3
00:00:05.860 --> 00:00:09.000
everyone has enjoyed the first

4
00:00:09.660 --> 00:00:12.720
day or day and a half, I guess it started yesterday.

5
00:00:13.920 --> 00:00:17.900
I'm excited for today's session. This is a methods

6
00:00:17.940 --> 00:00:21.060
workshop on cancer

7
00:00:21.070 --> 00:00:25.040
metabolism, and we have three speakers in the session.

8
00:00:25.460 --> 00:00:28.570
The way we're going to run the session is each speaker will give their talk, and

9
00:00:28.600 --> 00:00:32.341
then we'll do, depending on how long the speaker talks,

10
00:00:32.820 --> 00:00:36.629
roughly five to 10 minutes worth of questions for each speaker.

11
00:00:36.680 --> 00:00:40.600
And the goal is to end on time at around, like what is

12
00:00:40.620 --> 00:00:44.300
it? 2:30, around 4:00. So, let's get right to it.

13
00:00:44.360 --> 00:00:47.800
Our first speaker is Josh Rabinowitz, who's going to talk about spatial

14
00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:50.300
metabolomics of pancreas and breast cancer. Josh.

15
00:00:58.460 --> 00:01:00.680
Thanks, Matt, and nice to see all of you.

16
00:01:02.440 --> 00:01:06.120
The tumor is a battlefield between the forces of good,

17
00:01:06.680 --> 00:01:10.240
our anti-tumor immune system, sometimes scarce good,

18
00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:14.100
and evil, the cancer cells and supporting cells.

19
00:01:14.720 --> 00:01:17.670
And key to the battle are the supply lines,

20
00:01:18.100 --> 00:01:21.840
metabolism. And we have amazing technologies for

21
00:01:21.880 --> 00:01:25.380
measuring metabolism at the whole tumor level, from imaging

22
00:01:25.480 --> 00:01:29.420
technologies like FDG-PET, to

23
00:01:29.500 --> 00:01:33.010
ex vivo technologies like metabolomics that can look

24
00:01:33.040 --> 00:01:36.050
deeply at every metabolite in the tumor specimen.

25
00:01:36.780 --> 00:01:39.600
The challenge is that those technologies don't tell us what's

26
00:01:39.640 --> 00:01:43.610
available to the different cell types within the tumor, and that's what

27
00:01:43.640 --> 00:01:45.020
I'm going to talk to you about today.

28
00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:49.340
In particular, I'm going to talk about three questions.

29
00:01:49.400 --> 00:01:53.200
So how do metabolite levels differ across different cell types in the tumor?

30
00:01:54.320 --> 00:01:58.280
How is energy made? What substrates are providing energy in different

31
00:01:58.320 --> 00:02:02.080
cell types in the tumor? And how can what we learn

32
00:02:02.260 --> 00:02:06.140
from those two types of analyses be integrated with our

33
00:02:06.300 --> 00:02:10.200
knowledge to think about ways of attacking tumors in the clinic?

34
00:02:11.880 --> 00:02:14.200
And I'm going to talk about two technologies.

35
00:02:14.700 --> 00:02:18.440
The first technology is the one that's in the title, spatial metabolomics,

36
00:02:18.900 --> 00:02:21.620
based on MALDI imaging mass spectrometry.

37
00:02:22.800 --> 00:02:23.920
What is this? Alright.

38
00:02:25.100 --> 00:02:29.020
MALDI imaging starts with a frozen section, flash frozen

39
00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:33.240
tumor tissue, cut into an approximately

40
00:02:33.300 --> 00:02:37.240
10-micron thick slice, just as you would do for histology, but fresh tissue.

41
00:02:38.160 --> 00:02:41.240
Then it's coated with an organic matrix that

42
00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:45.120
absorbs UV laser light, and so this is the M and A in

43
00:02:45.160 --> 00:02:48.660
MALDI, matrix assisted. So when that matrix

44
00:02:48.760 --> 00:02:52.680
absorbs the UV laser light, the L for laser in MALDI,

45
00:02:53.280 --> 00:02:57.210
then the matrix gets very hot, almost explodes off of

46
00:02:57.240 --> 00:03:01.140
the surface, carrying with it gas phase metabolite and lipid ions.

47
00:03:01.460 --> 00:03:04.480
That's the D and the I, the desorption

48
00:03:04.560 --> 00:03:08.430
ionization process, that allows us to get, for every

49
00:03:08.700 --> 00:03:12.640
5 or 10 micron sized spot on the tissue section,

50
00:03:13.040 --> 00:03:17.000
a mass spectrum reflecting the metabolites and lipids present at that

51
00:03:17.020 --> 00:03:18.240
particular location.

52
00:03:20.240 --> 00:03:23.200
This is a image made with our latest MALDI

53
00:03:23.520 --> 00:03:27.420
technology by the guru, technically, in this technique in my

54
00:03:27.520 --> 00:03:30.000
lab, Lei Somara, who's on the job market right now.

55
00:03:30.540 --> 00:03:33.860
And this is looking at the intestine at effectively single cell

56
00:03:33.900 --> 00:03:37.260
resolution. The blue is a fatty acid that's enriched in the

57
00:03:37.300 --> 00:03:40.120
epithelial cells of the intestinal lining.

58
00:03:40.160 --> 00:03:42.220
You see the finger-like projections.

59
00:03:42.260 --> 00:03:44.730
There's a single cell layer of epithelial cells.

60
00:03:45.240 --> 00:03:48.640
And then in red, you're seeing false color code for the

61
00:03:48.680 --> 00:03:52.320
extent of uptake of fructose that was

62
00:03:52.360 --> 00:03:55.980
given in isotope labeled form. So it's heavy fructose, so we can track

63
00:03:56.020 --> 00:03:57.200
exactly where it's going

64
00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:01.580
and see where it is taken in and phosphorylated to make fructose

65
00:04:01.780 --> 00:04:05.360
1-phosphate. And you see that fructose is being processed

66
00:04:05.440 --> 00:04:09.360
preferentially in the bottom of the intestinal

67
00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:12.940
villi towards the crypts, where

68
00:04:12.980 --> 00:04:15.040
colorectal cancer tends to occur.

69
00:04:15.240 --> 00:04:19.079
And fructose is one of the nutrients that when we take it in the diet, is

70
00:04:19.120 --> 00:04:21.860
most strongly associated with risk of colorectal cancer.

71
00:04:23.980 --> 00:04:26.520
So what's happening actually in tumors?

72
00:04:27.480 --> 00:04:29.400
I'm going to start with breast cancer.

73
00:04:29.840 --> 00:04:33.730
In particular, I'm going to start with hormone receptor positive, HER2 new

74
00:04:33.820 --> 00:04:37.490
negative breast cancer, and that's all the breast cancer type I'll talk about in

75
00:04:37.520 --> 00:04:40.990
this talk. You see here a clinical team that's made this

76
00:04:41.020 --> 00:04:44.930
possible, as well as the postdoc in my lab, Meera Gupta, who's done all

77
00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:46.020
of the tumor work.

78
00:04:47.140 --> 00:04:50.340
And so breast cancer has a relatively straightforward

79
00:04:51.320 --> 00:04:55.180
histology. You see the ducts that are the breast

80
00:04:55.220 --> 00:04:58.960
cancer cells, some fibrosis, and here there's effectively no

81
00:04:59.020 --> 00:05:02.940
force for good, okay? There's almost no immune cells detectable.

82
00:05:04.320 --> 00:05:07.800
Then on the right-hand side here, you

83
00:05:07.860 --> 00:05:10.640
see a MALDI image of two lipids.

84
00:05:11.480 --> 00:05:15.460
And the remarkable thing is that these lipids encode exactly the

85
00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:19.180
fibroblast versus the epithelial component of the tumor.

86
00:05:20.880 --> 00:05:22.260
What's different in these lipids?

87
00:05:22.300 --> 00:05:26.080
Well, they're both phosphatidylethanolamine lipids, that's the PE.

88
00:05:26.120 --> 00:05:29.740
What they differ in is in the fatty acid tails attached to

89
00:05:29.800 --> 00:05:33.510
this PE. The one in red that marks epithelium, and this

90
00:05:33.620 --> 00:05:37.280
epithelial derived breast cancer, has two

91
00:05:37.320 --> 00:05:41.120
18:1 tails, 18:1 meaning 18 carbons with one

92
00:05:41.200 --> 00:05:44.820
double bond. That's oleate or the olive oil

93
00:05:44.860 --> 00:05:46.240
characteristic fatty acid.

94
00:05:47.080 --> 00:05:51.020
And then the fibroblast marking lipid

95
00:05:51.140 --> 00:05:55.100
has more carbons total, one saturated tail, and then one

96
00:05:55.160 --> 00:05:59.030
unsaturated tail, that's omega-6, effectively a seed oil type

97
00:05:59.030 --> 00:06:02.800
fatty acid tail. And so what we learn from this image, first of all,

98
00:06:03.300 --> 00:06:07.060
is that there are very specific lipids that, for

99
00:06:07.100 --> 00:06:10.804
reasons we don't understand yetSelectively mark

100
00:06:10.814 --> 00:06:12.564
different cell types within the tumor.

101
00:06:12.744 --> 00:06:16.464
A key ongoing goal is to figure out what's the biochemical basis for

102
00:06:16.504 --> 00:06:20.414
this lipid specialization, and is this actually driving

103
00:06:20.744 --> 00:06:22.084
cell fate in the body?

104
00:06:23.164 --> 00:06:26.624
Before we answer those questions, we can still use these lipids effectively as

105
00:06:26.684 --> 00:06:30.434
markers to tell us what cell type we're looking at when we then go on and look at

106
00:06:30.464 --> 00:06:34.374
metabolites. And I'm going to talk today about very classical metabolites like

107
00:06:34.384 --> 00:06:34.924
glucose,

108
00:06:35.744 --> 00:06:39.724
in the textbook, the beginning of making energy, ATP, the end

109
00:06:39.784 --> 00:06:43.504
of metabolic making energy, the high-energy molecule that you may be aiming

110
00:06:43.564 --> 00:06:43.843
for.

111
00:06:44.704 --> 00:06:48.394
And so if we look in breast cancer, what I think you can see quite clearly,

112
00:06:48.584 --> 00:06:51.944
again, these are all false color images where the brightness of the color

113
00:06:52.344 --> 00:06:56.064
indicates the strength of the metabolite signal, is that

114
00:06:56.124 --> 00:06:59.604
glucose is depleted where the cancer cells are within breast

115
00:06:59.764 --> 00:07:03.664
tumors, and ATP is increased. And we see this

116
00:07:03.724 --> 00:07:06.864
across all patients and all segments of tumors that we look at.

117
00:07:06.904 --> 00:07:10.764
On the bottom is an overlay. When you see red and green separate, that

118
00:07:10.824 --> 00:07:14.344
shows that the cancer cell marker is spatially distinct from the glucose.

119
00:07:14.404 --> 00:07:17.844
Glucose is depleted in cancer. When you see yellow, that's

120
00:07:17.944 --> 00:07:21.824
overlap. So the ATP is enriched in the cancer cells compared to

121
00:07:21.864 --> 00:07:22.724
the fibroblast.

122
00:07:25.324 --> 00:07:28.864
So we have glucose depletion. That makes sense. Cancer cells love glucose.

123
00:07:29.004 --> 00:07:31.204
Warburg taught us that 100 years ago.

124
00:07:31.284 --> 00:07:35.204
And the first thing they do when they take in glucose is make glucose phosphate,

125
00:07:35.264 --> 00:07:38.684
and it's effectively a trapped version of glucose phosphate that allows

126
00:07:38.784 --> 00:07:42.164
FDG-PET imaging. So we said, can we see glucose phosphate also

127
00:07:42.744 --> 00:07:44.484
in these images?

128
00:07:45.584 --> 00:07:49.284
And from a purely technical perspective, kind of is the

129
00:07:49.364 --> 00:07:53.334
answer. So we get a beautiful-looking image at the mass of glucose

130
00:07:53.384 --> 00:07:57.344
phosphate that's beautifully in the cancer cell, exactly what we wanted to see.

131
00:07:58.044 --> 00:08:01.884
But after a great deal of work, we realized that there is an artifact going

132
00:08:01.944 --> 00:08:05.684
on here. And the artifact is that we can get

133
00:08:06.324 --> 00:08:09.964
an ion at the mass of glucose phosphate multiple

134
00:08:09.984 --> 00:08:13.194
ways. The way we want to get it is because there's actually glucose phosphate in

135
00:08:13.224 --> 00:08:16.984
the tumor. But when you hit laser energy into these tumor

136
00:08:17.064 --> 00:08:18.644
slices, you can break things apart.

137
00:08:18.704 --> 00:08:22.684
And one thing you can break apart is phospholipids, and if you break off the head

138
00:08:22.744 --> 00:08:26.364
group of phosphatidylinositols, you can get glucose phosphate.

139
00:08:26.704 --> 00:08:30.384
When you do that, you also get a similar metabolite that's lacking

140
00:08:30.464 --> 00:08:34.284
water that you do not get from glycolysis. You see these two images are the same.

141
00:08:34.704 --> 00:08:38.304
When those two images are the same, you know you're looking at an artifact, a lipid

142
00:08:38.404 --> 00:08:40.704
fragment, not the actual glycolytic intermediate.

143
00:08:40.764 --> 00:08:42.944
So that's a little technology warning for you all.

144
00:08:44.444 --> 00:08:46.633
Okay. Let's go on now to pancreas cancer.

145
00:08:46.744 --> 00:08:50.133
Pancreas cancer is histologically much more complex.

146
00:08:50.844 --> 00:08:54.044
In this case, we have a more sparse battlefield.

147
00:08:54.064 --> 00:08:58.004
The cancer cells are relatively rare, as you see in these little

148
00:08:58.104 --> 00:09:01.904
red islands within the tumor. Lots of fibrosis, and there are immune

149
00:09:01.984 --> 00:09:05.924
cells, but often immunosuppressive immune cells and not exactly where you

150
00:09:05.964 --> 00:09:09.144
want them, typically not surrounding the cancer cells.

151
00:09:09.184 --> 00:09:12.794
We can go to the exact same lipid markers that we used to define the

152
00:09:12.824 --> 00:09:16.684
epithelial breast cancer, and they perfectly light up the epithelial pancreas

153
00:09:16.744 --> 00:09:17.504
cancer cells.

154
00:09:18.604 --> 00:09:22.284
Same thing for the fibrosis in pancreas cancer, exact same lipid.

155
00:09:22.654 --> 00:09:24.864
And now I'm going to introduce one more lipid.

156
00:09:24.874 --> 00:09:28.674
This has an omega-3 tail, effectively a fish oil tail,

157
00:09:28.784 --> 00:09:30.574
and that lights up pretty well

158
00:09:31.804 --> 00:09:34.924
different classes of CD45 positive immune cells.

159
00:09:37.324 --> 00:09:39.724
What's the message now in pancreas cancer?

160
00:09:39.764 --> 00:09:43.704
We're looking at three cell types, fibrosis, immune cells, and

161
00:09:43.784 --> 00:09:44.544
cancer cells.

162
00:09:45.664 --> 00:09:49.244
And so if you look here in the glucose image, you'll see areas where there's

163
00:09:49.304 --> 00:09:53.104
clearly glucose depletion, and those correspond both

164
00:09:53.164 --> 00:09:56.644
to this lymphocyte-rich immune infiltrate,

165
00:09:56.684 --> 00:10:00.424
effectively a tertiary lymphoid organ within the pancreas cancer.

166
00:10:00.804 --> 00:10:04.404
It's depleted for glucose, as is the areas where you have

167
00:10:04.444 --> 00:10:08.304
epithelial cancer, and those exact same areas are

168
00:10:08.504 --> 00:10:11.004
rich in high-energy adenosine nucleotides.

169
00:10:11.064 --> 00:10:15.004
In this case, I'm using ADP as a surrogate for ATP because ATP

170
00:10:15.084 --> 00:10:18.864
fragments to ADP. ADP is much easier to detect in MALDI

171
00:10:19.304 --> 00:10:22.564
than ATP. I'll show you a bit more evidence that these really are high-energy

172
00:10:22.684 --> 00:10:24.824
charge regions as we go along.

173
00:10:26.924 --> 00:10:29.984
And this just shows the overlay for the immune marker.

174
00:10:30.124 --> 00:10:34.044
You see the immune marker in an area with low glucose

175
00:10:34.344 --> 00:10:36.224
and high ADP.

176
00:10:39.084 --> 00:10:42.594
So in general, what we see in these tumors is that almost every

177
00:10:42.624 --> 00:10:46.584
metabolic feature that we see in cancer cells is mimicked in

178
00:10:46.624 --> 00:10:49.964
immune cells. So we see very stark differences between

179
00:10:50.024 --> 00:10:52.784
fibroblasts and either cancer cells or immune cells.

180
00:10:52.864 --> 00:10:56.234
But as we've seen so often in the cancer metabolism world,

181
00:10:56.604 --> 00:10:59.834
cancer cells and immune cells vary metabolically similar,

182
00:11:00.044 --> 00:11:04.004
unfortunately. One striking difference, and this is sialic

183
00:11:04.164 --> 00:11:06.604
acid. This is not really a free metabolite.

184
00:11:07.113 --> 00:11:10.674
This is an unusual sugar that modifies

185
00:11:11.544 --> 00:11:15.364
both proteins and lipids, and it's a sugar that effectively

186
00:11:15.464 --> 00:11:19.404
acts as a 'don't eat me' signal, a turn immunosuppressive signal to

187
00:11:19.444 --> 00:11:20.184
immune cells.

188
00:11:21.064 --> 00:11:24.704
It's shown here in two different patient slices at two different magnifications

189
00:11:25.144 --> 00:11:28.984
from pancreas cancer. And what I want you to notice is wherever you see this green

190
00:11:29.084 --> 00:11:32.484
sialic acid signal, you see no immune cells.

191
00:11:33.364 --> 00:11:37.244
Absolutely none in the region here where you see

192
00:11:37.284 --> 00:11:41.264
lots of sialic acid. And then here there's actually an interesting case where

193
00:11:41.304 --> 00:11:44.944
you see immune cells surrounding PDAC cells, perhaps even

194
00:11:45.024 --> 00:11:48.724
killing these PDAC cells. But right adjacent, you see other PDAC

195
00:11:48.784 --> 00:11:51.864
cells that are secreting sialic acid, and they're completely

196
00:11:51.924 --> 00:11:55.824
unmolested by immune cells. And again, we see this reliably across

197
00:11:55.844 --> 00:11:56.304
patients.

198
00:11:58.344 --> 00:12:02.304
Overall, what we see is that glucose, and not just

199
00:12:02.364 --> 00:12:06.144
glucose, other fuels like glutamine are low in the cancer

200
00:12:06.224 --> 00:12:06.644
cells,

201
00:12:07.584 --> 00:12:11.324
and that ADP is high, and there's a high ADP to AMP

202
00:12:11.424 --> 00:12:14.204
ratio, again, saying these are actually high-energy charge regions.

203
00:12:14.344 --> 00:12:18.084
Uric acid is low. Uric acid very reliably goes up when cells are under

204
00:12:18.144 --> 00:12:21.824
energy stress. And this all says that the cancer cells are

205
00:12:22.464 --> 00:12:25.936
fuel poor but energy adequate.And this shows this is

206
00:12:25.996 --> 00:12:29.226
exactly true over both breast cancer and pancreas cancer.

207
00:12:29.376 --> 00:12:33.196
Every trend that we see between fibroblasts and cancer cells within the

208
00:12:34.316 --> 00:12:37.626
tumor microenvironment is effectively preserved.

209
00:12:39.296 --> 00:12:43.116
So how do nutrient-poor cancer cells maintain adequate energy charge?

210
00:12:44.036 --> 00:12:47.716
And part of this is because the cancer cells are masters at

211
00:12:47.756 --> 00:12:51.136
getting nutrients out of the environment, as are the

212
00:12:51.236 --> 00:12:55.116
activated immune cells. Part of it is that cancer cells are masters at

213
00:12:55.196 --> 00:12:59.126
growing with relatively little energy utilization,

214
00:12:59.176 --> 00:13:02.736
and they do this by eschewing energy-intensive functions of the

215
00:13:02.796 --> 00:13:06.556
tissue of origin. And you see the paper there by Carolyn Bartman, you can read on

216
00:13:06.596 --> 00:13:10.476
that topic. And finally, of course, they are consuming glucose, and that

217
00:13:10.516 --> 00:13:12.616
is giving them some glycolytic ATP.

218
00:13:13.856 --> 00:13:17.816
So we really wanted to go deeper into understanding the fuel sources in these

219
00:13:17.856 --> 00:13:19.996
cell types, and for that, I'm going to switch to mouse

220
00:13:22.636 --> 00:13:26.236
and really focus on the fuels that are feeding into the

221
00:13:26.276 --> 00:13:30.136
TCA cycle, because when we've carefully analyzed where most ATP

222
00:13:30.155 --> 00:13:33.956
is coming from, not just in the normal body, but also in tumors, in the

223
00:13:34.056 --> 00:13:37.336
vast majority of contexts, it's through aerobic

224
00:13:37.396 --> 00:13:40.535
metabolism driven by TCA turning.

225
00:13:41.086 --> 00:13:44.486
And this is work of another postdoc, Christian Piece, and he's going to look at a

226
00:13:44.576 --> 00:13:48.496
bunch of different 13C level substrates and how they feed into

227
00:13:48.536 --> 00:13:51.196
different cell types within the tumor microenvironment.

228
00:13:53.096 --> 00:13:54.956
And the challenge in doing this is if you just

229
00:13:55.776 --> 00:13:59.236
grow your tumors, do your tracing, and sort the cells, then the

230
00:13:59.276 --> 00:14:01.976
metabolites during the sorting process can leak out.

231
00:14:02.016 --> 00:14:05.796
They can even trade from one cell type to another, and you don't have confidence in

232
00:14:05.836 --> 00:14:09.696
what you're seeing. And so to address this, we're going to use

233
00:14:09.736 --> 00:14:13.016
two amino acids that are in rapid exchange with the TCA cycle,

234
00:14:13.076 --> 00:14:16.766
aspartate and glutamate, as our readouts for TCA labeling,

235
00:14:17.016 --> 00:14:20.606
and we're going to use those amino acids trapped in protein, effectively using

236
00:14:20.636 --> 00:14:23.676
protein as a vault to store our labeling information.

237
00:14:23.696 --> 00:14:26.676
And this is a technique that I first learned about at a meeting from Matt Vander

238
00:14:26.696 --> 00:14:27.656
Heiden, our chair here.

239
00:14:29.856 --> 00:14:32.936
And so there was one tweak to make this technique work well, and that's we got to

240
00:14:32.956 --> 00:14:35.255
get our information out of the vault also.

241
00:14:35.676 --> 00:14:39.456
And there was a challenge in doing this because in hydrolyzing protein, you tend to

242
00:14:39.516 --> 00:14:43.236
interconvert aspartate and asparagine and glutamate and glutamine.

243
00:14:43.636 --> 00:14:46.936
And ultimately, we were able to solve this with the help of our Nobel Prize-winning

244
00:14:47.036 --> 00:14:50.496
chemistry colleague, David MacMillan, by doing a deuterated

245
00:14:50.576 --> 00:14:54.476
reductive step on the intact protein to clearly mark all the aspartate and

246
00:14:54.516 --> 00:14:58.166
glutamate residues. Once we had that in place, we could run this technique,

247
00:14:58.656 --> 00:15:02.586
and we could get the exact same answers from bulk tissues as we'd gotten from all

248
00:15:02.616 --> 00:15:06.596
of our classic tracing experiments where we looked directly at something like

249
00:15:06.616 --> 00:15:09.816
citrate or malate. Key to making this work is also

250
00:15:09.876 --> 00:15:13.825
co-infusing a central amino acid, and

251
00:15:13.836 --> 00:15:17.076
we use valine labeled as a position that never enters the TCA

252
00:15:17.116 --> 00:15:20.976
cycle as a marker for the amount of protein synthesized in each cell

253
00:15:20.996 --> 00:15:24.946
type so that we aren't measuring protein synthesis, we're just measuring the

254
00:15:25.036 --> 00:15:27.276
feedstocks of the TCA cycle.

255
00:15:29.516 --> 00:15:32.956
When we've done this at the bulk level, one of the most important

256
00:15:33.016 --> 00:15:36.996
messages that we learned was that almost every cell type in the body

257
00:15:37.196 --> 00:15:41.126
uses lactate as a major fuel. You can see this

258
00:15:41.556 --> 00:15:45.536
at the top here. Every cell type in the body uses lactate to

259
00:15:45.596 --> 00:15:48.016
fuel the TCA cycle about one-third.

260
00:15:48.346 --> 00:15:52.266
And this is true also in tumors that we've looked at in mice, and it's

261
00:15:52.296 --> 00:15:55.876
true in lung cancers that Ralph DeBerardinis has looked at

262
00:15:56.276 --> 00:15:59.816
in people. And so there's effectively a cycle where glucose that we eat

263
00:16:00.276 --> 00:16:04.216
is converted in glycolytic cells within the body, mainly working muscle

264
00:16:04.276 --> 00:16:08.156
into lactate, then fuels all sorts of cells in the body that are not

265
00:16:08.616 --> 00:16:11.016
have the permission to use glucose.

266
00:16:12.916 --> 00:16:16.576
Now, within the tumor microenvironment, is this universal use of lactate as a

267
00:16:16.636 --> 00:16:18.696
fuel actually the rule?

268
00:16:19.516 --> 00:16:23.456
There have been many high-profile papers over the past few years saying that

269
00:16:23.536 --> 00:16:27.376
immunosuppressive immune cells particularly love to

270
00:16:27.436 --> 00:16:30.676
use lactate as fuel, and this is part of why high lactate in the tumor

271
00:16:30.736 --> 00:16:34.516
microenvironment is a problem. And one of the most impactful of

272
00:16:34.556 --> 00:16:38.376
these papers came from Greg Dougherty's lab, and you can see the

273
00:16:38.416 --> 00:16:42.355
tracing data, this time done ex vivo, okay, comparing use

274
00:16:42.416 --> 00:16:46.235
of lactate as a fuel in the FoxP3 positive

275
00:16:46.536 --> 00:16:49.056
Treg cells compared to T effector cells.

276
00:16:49.086 --> 00:16:53.056
And you see what looks like a big difference. But does this hold in vivo?

277
00:16:54.096 --> 00:16:56.506
And what we find is absolutely not.

278
00:16:57.216 --> 00:17:00.986
In our in vivo studies in MC38 cancer cells, at

279
00:17:01.036 --> 00:17:04.696
least in this tumor type, we see lactate is a

280
00:17:04.757 --> 00:17:08.616
universal fuel. Just like it's universal against all organs of the body, it's

281
00:17:08.636 --> 00:17:11.676
universal across all cell types in the tumor with frankly

282
00:17:11.737 --> 00:17:15.656
indistinguishable contributions between different tumor cell types,

283
00:17:15.816 --> 00:17:19.086
including using this Treg reporter mouse so we can very cleanly

284
00:17:19.116 --> 00:17:22.916
compare Tregs to effector T cells, and they have

285
00:17:22.977 --> 00:17:25.036
identical lactate contributions.

286
00:17:26.286 --> 00:17:30.096
Now, not everything contributes identically, and one of the most interesting

287
00:17:30.116 --> 00:17:33.776
differences that we found is specific utilization of

288
00:17:33.956 --> 00:17:37.596
3-hydroxybutyrate, also known as beta-hydroxybutyrate or a ketone

289
00:17:37.656 --> 00:17:37.976
body,

290
00:17:38.936 --> 00:17:42.756
by the CD8 positive T cells within the tumor.

291
00:17:43.076 --> 00:17:46.516
And this aligns very nicely with data from many labs

292
00:17:47.196 --> 00:17:51.076
showing that 3-hydroxybutyrate can be a powerful both fuel

293
00:17:51.156 --> 00:17:54.936
and epigenetic modifier, a subtle donor for epigenetics

294
00:17:55.036 --> 00:17:58.936
in effector T cells. An example of this from Rusty Jones

295
00:17:59.016 --> 00:18:01.736
I think is particularly nice because of the genetic component.

296
00:18:02.236 --> 00:18:05.896
He uses caloric restriction in order to get better

297
00:18:05.976 --> 00:18:09.716
antitumor immunity that you see in the blue line, so

298
00:18:09.776 --> 00:18:13.396
that mice live longer in a way that's dependent on their immune

299
00:18:13.436 --> 00:18:17.366
system and that caloric restriction is inducing 3-hydroxybutyrate

300
00:18:17.366 --> 00:18:21.236
via ketosis, and that extension in lifespan is lost

301
00:18:21.616 --> 00:18:25.476
if you make the T cells in that mouse incapable

302
00:18:25.556 --> 00:18:26.376
of using

303
00:18:26.556 --> 00:18:30.288
3-hydroxybutyrate.So

304
00:18:30.308 --> 00:18:31.868
within MC38 tumors,

305
00:18:32.728 --> 00:18:34.388
I showed you that all cells use lactate.

306
00:18:34.408 --> 00:18:36.998
We get similar results for glucose and glutamine.

307
00:18:38.148 --> 00:18:42.128
Immune cells use acetate. I didn't show you that, but they use it much more than at

308
00:18:42.148 --> 00:18:45.458
least MC38 tumor cells. And CD8 T cells,

309
00:18:45.868 --> 00:18:47.888
particularly like 3-hydroxybutyrate.

310
00:18:48.628 --> 00:18:52.028
And putting together then the two parts of the talk, you can

311
00:18:52.108 --> 00:18:56.018
see that the cancer cells are glucose-starved, and

312
00:18:56.048 --> 00:18:59.908
so it might be good to stress them more by making them even more glucose-starved.

313
00:19:00.418 --> 00:19:03.188
The T cells are really liking 3-hydroxybutyrate.

314
00:19:03.488 --> 00:19:07.388
And of course, a single diet can combine these two features of low

315
00:19:07.448 --> 00:19:11.308
glucose and high 3-hydroxybutyrate, and that's a ketogenic diet.

316
00:19:12.588 --> 00:19:16.088
And so we wanted to see, could this actually help in

317
00:19:16.168 --> 00:19:17.108
pancreas cancer?

318
00:19:19.508 --> 00:19:22.928
For those of you who are not familiar with ketogenic diet, it's a very high fat,

319
00:19:23.428 --> 00:19:26.668
moderate protein, very low carbohydrate diet.

320
00:19:26.708 --> 00:19:30.568
Kind of like what's on the screen, except more bacon and less asparagus and salmon.

321
00:19:30.628 --> 00:19:30.948
Okay?

322
00:19:32.828 --> 00:19:36.728
This diet lowers glucose a little bit in the bloodstream.

323
00:19:37.188 --> 00:19:41.028
But what's very important here, I think, is that intramural glucose in pancreas

324
00:19:41.068 --> 00:19:43.588
cancer is way lower than blood glucose.

325
00:19:43.638 --> 00:19:47.488
And at least in mouse experiments, proportionally falls more in

326
00:19:47.508 --> 00:19:51.288
ketogenic diet than does blood glucose, all the way to below one

327
00:19:51.368 --> 00:19:55.268
millimolar, so you have genuine glucose restriction within

328
00:19:55.308 --> 00:19:55.808
the tumor.

329
00:19:57.668 --> 00:20:01.548
What happens when you combine this with other stressors like a targeted

330
00:20:01.558 --> 00:20:04.668
therapy, like a PI3K inhibitor or classical

331
00:20:04.708 --> 00:20:07.638
chemotherapy, in this case, gemcitabine,

332
00:20:08.088 --> 00:20:09.458
abraxane, and

333
00:20:10.908 --> 00:20:11.448
cisplatin.

334
00:20:12.528 --> 00:20:15.708
So what we saw i-in experiments, this is Lou Cantley's

335
00:20:15.948 --> 00:20:19.458
experiments that informed the field a great deal, is that the

336
00:20:19.528 --> 00:20:23.088
combination of PI3K inhibitor and ketogenic

337
00:20:23.148 --> 00:20:26.708
diet could profoundly slow pancreas cancer growth.

338
00:20:27.158 --> 00:20:31.128
And similarly, some positive results combining it with chemotherapy in

339
00:20:31.168 --> 00:20:31.798
our hands.

340
00:20:33.168 --> 00:20:36.888
Over the intervening years, we've learned that there was a complication in these

341
00:20:36.908 --> 00:20:40.848
experiments, and that's the one we were comparing standard mouse chow to

342
00:20:40.868 --> 00:20:44.768
ketogenic diet. The mouse chow was loaded with all sorts of stuff

343
00:20:44.808 --> 00:20:48.728
from plants, all sorts of plant phytochemicals, whereas the ketogenic diet

344
00:20:48.768 --> 00:20:51.988
was clean. It was clean milk protein and oil.

345
00:20:52.548 --> 00:20:54.688
And all these phytochemicals end up mattering.

346
00:20:55.108 --> 00:20:58.348
And the way that they most obviously matter is they affect liver drug

347
00:20:58.408 --> 00:21:01.968
metabolism. And so one reason why you were getting so much better

348
00:21:02.048 --> 00:21:05.538
responses here in the ketogenic diet context was the

349
00:21:05.928 --> 00:21:09.908
liver drug metabolism was slowed down by the lack of phytochemicals

350
00:21:09.928 --> 00:21:13.668
in the ketogenic diet, and so that was one factor.

351
00:21:14.548 --> 00:21:16.248
But perhaps fortuitously,

352
00:21:17.148 --> 00:21:21.108
uh, we didn't learn about that fast enough, and so we went forward

353
00:21:21.168 --> 00:21:24.988
to do a clinical trial. Uh, this is the work of Gail Jamieson, Dan

354
00:21:25.008 --> 00:21:28.808
Von Hoff, and many other colleagues who worked incredibly

355
00:21:28.848 --> 00:21:32.368
hard to pull this trial off. Looking at first-line

356
00:21:32.388 --> 00:21:36.168
metastatic pancreas cancer, treating with state-of-the-art triple

357
00:21:36.188 --> 00:21:40.128
chemotherapy, this was before RAS inhibitors, with or without

358
00:21:40.248 --> 00:21:43.888
a supervised carbohydrate-restricted diet.

359
00:21:44.068 --> 00:21:47.988
Patients made their own food, uh, but with supervision from a

360
00:21:48.028 --> 00:21:51.748
company called Virta Health that was doing electronic monitoring of their ketosis.

361
00:21:52.208 --> 00:21:56.068
The trial was never powered to give a definitive answer, right, but it had

362
00:21:56.108 --> 00:21:59.618
16 valuable patients per arm randomized.

363
00:21:59.648 --> 00:22:02.248
And it's trying to give us a clue, is this worth pursuing more?

364
00:22:03.148 --> 00:22:05.748
And I think the upshot i-is very much so.

365
00:22:06.208 --> 00:22:09.448
So on the left here, you see the progression-free survival data.

366
00:22:10.028 --> 00:22:14.008
There's about a three-month benefit in terms of progression-free survival

367
00:22:14.088 --> 00:22:18.028
in the ketogenic diet group. On the right, you see overall survival,

368
00:22:18.368 --> 00:22:22.248
again, favoring the ketogenic diet group with a little bit more than

369
00:22:22.288 --> 00:22:26.248
three-month benefit. Of course, we want to give more than three months to our

370
00:22:26.308 --> 00:22:29.468
pancreas cancer patients. But if you look at the clinical benefits that were

371
00:22:29.488 --> 00:22:33.457
achieved when gemcitabine was introduced, when abraxane was introduced,

372
00:22:33.848 --> 00:22:35.868
these were about three-month clinical benefits.

373
00:22:36.608 --> 00:22:40.508
RAS inhibitors, thankfully, are going to do more, but they're not going to do

374
00:22:40.588 --> 00:22:44.168
so many fold more. So this is a meaningful benefit in the context of pancreas

375
00:22:44.248 --> 00:22:44.688
cancer.

376
00:22:46.148 --> 00:22:49.528
It's particularly meaningful given that this is a very tough diet.

377
00:22:49.688 --> 00:22:52.968
A minority of the time were patients actually in ketosis.

378
00:22:53.008 --> 00:22:56.588
When they were in ketosis, they were not in very deep ketosis, and there was a

379
00:22:56.648 --> 00:22:59.948
correlation between the extent of ketosis and longer

380
00:22:59.988 --> 00:23:01.528
survival in the trial.

381
00:23:02.428 --> 00:23:06.368
So with that, I'm leaving you with the idea that tumors are glucose depleted,

382
00:23:06.468 --> 00:23:10.288
especially around both immune cells and the cancer

383
00:23:10.368 --> 00:23:14.328
cells, that the intramural T cells are avid 3HB

384
00:23:14.368 --> 00:23:18.128
consumers, and that therefore, the combination of

385
00:23:18.188 --> 00:23:21.868
lower glucose, higher 3HB, and ketogenic diet is something worthier of further

386
00:23:21.908 --> 00:23:25.518
clinical exploration. I want to thank the very many people and

