00:29:27.832 --> 00:29:30.292
metabolism in the ketogenic diet. Thank you.

507
00:29:30.552 --> 00:29:31.712
Okay, great. Thanks so much.

508
00:29:38.432 --> 00:29:40.412
Okay. Our next speaker,

509
00:29:41.572 --> 00:29:45.132
whose slides will be coming up shortly, is Gerta Hoxha

510
00:29:45.392 --> 00:29:49.332
from UT Southwestern, and she's going to tell us about

511
00:29:49.392 --> 00:29:52.032
metabolic regulation of cancer cell growth. Gerta.

512
00:29:53.052 --> 00:29:56.792
Thanks, Matt. First of all, I want to thank Matt for the kind invitation to be

513
00:29:56.852 --> 00:29:59.532
here and present some of our lab work.

514
00:30:00.812 --> 00:30:03.472
My lab is interested in decoding metabolism.

515
00:30:03.552 --> 00:30:07.392
We're interested in the fundamentals of metabolism in the context of cancer

516
00:30:07.532 --> 00:30:11.272
and metabolic disorders. And as we all know, metabolism is

517
00:30:11.372 --> 00:30:14.792
vastly complicated, but at the same time, is highly regulated.

518
00:30:15.292 --> 00:30:19.162
However, metabolic processes get deregulated in

519
00:30:19.252 --> 00:30:23.092
response to stress, bad diet, genetic factors, and this can lead

520
00:30:23.212 --> 00:30:27.148
to cancer and metabolic syndrome.And in the vast

521
00:30:27.188 --> 00:30:31.148
realm of metabolism, my lab has been particularly interested in nucleotide

522
00:30:31.188 --> 00:30:34.518
metabolism. Both the classical nucleotides, purine and

523
00:30:34.568 --> 00:30:38.148
pyrimidines, which are part of the

524
00:30:39.168 --> 00:30:42.668
genetic material, make RNA and DNA, but are also important

525
00:30:42.788 --> 00:30:46.768
factors for energy generation. But we're also interested in other

526
00:30:46.868 --> 00:30:50.548
classes of nucleotides, and in particular in nucleotide redox

527
00:30:50.668 --> 00:30:53.768
cofactors, NADP and NADPH.

528
00:30:54.448 --> 00:30:57.468
NADPH is a dinucleotide, which is a

529
00:30:58.188 --> 00:31:00.228
general electron donor in the cell.

530
00:31:00.368 --> 00:31:03.968
It's really important for anabolic metabolism, but

531
00:31:04.068 --> 00:31:07.988
also generation of glutathione and thiredoxin to

532
00:31:08.028 --> 00:31:11.488
support antioxidant system. And in today's talk, I'll

533
00:31:11.508 --> 00:31:14.228
primarily focus on NADPH metabolism.

534
00:31:16.048 --> 00:31:19.968
So NADPH gives the cells the power to reduce, and

535
00:31:20.048 --> 00:31:21.228
one key characteristic

536
00:31:22.668 --> 00:31:25.668
of this metabolism is its

537
00:31:25.708 --> 00:31:29.468
compartmentalization. NADPH cofactors exist both in the

538
00:31:29.488 --> 00:31:31.508
cytosol, but also in the mitochondria.

539
00:31:32.248 --> 00:31:36.228
And primarily, we have studied these processes through the lens of two

540
00:31:36.238 --> 00:31:39.988
metabolic kinases, which are called NAD kinases.

541
00:31:40.048 --> 00:31:43.788
Mammalian cells encode two NAD kinases, cytosolic NADK,

542
00:31:44.068 --> 00:31:47.948
which phosphorylates NAD to generate NADP, which is then reduced

543
00:31:47.968 --> 00:31:51.828
on NADPH to support biosynthesis, but also inhibit ROS,

544
00:31:52.368 --> 00:31:56.268
as well as mitochondrial NDK2, which provides

545
00:31:56.288 --> 00:31:58.468
reducing power in the mitochondria.

546
00:31:59.208 --> 00:32:03.088
We've been primarily interested in these metabolic kinases because of their

547
00:32:03.128 --> 00:32:06.708
association with cancer, and they have emerged as

548
00:32:06.748 --> 00:32:09.488
important cancer targets. So for example,

549
00:32:10.468 --> 00:32:13.528
some previous work of mine has shown that cytosolic NADK

550
00:32:13.908 --> 00:32:17.728
is regulated by oncogenic PI3 kinase signaling, but

551
00:32:17.808 --> 00:32:21.708
also work from Blenis and Anagoma has shown that NAD

552
00:32:21.748 --> 00:32:25.248
kinase is also subject to regulation by other kinase

553
00:32:25.268 --> 00:32:29.148
signaling, such as KRAS. We've seen that these enzymes are upregulated

554
00:32:29.188 --> 00:32:32.908
in cancer, and mutations in NAD kinase can drive

555
00:32:33.568 --> 00:32:35.068
PDAC, but other

556
00:32:35.948 --> 00:32:36.528
cancers.

557
00:32:37.748 --> 00:32:41.728
More recently, about 10 years ago, another kinase was discovered, and this

558
00:32:41.808 --> 00:32:45.328
was NDK2. Similar to NDK,

559
00:32:45.588 --> 00:32:48.948
NDK2, if we look at cBioPortal data, it's also highly

560
00:32:48.988 --> 00:32:52.848
amplified in various types of cancer, and in particular is

561
00:32:52.908 --> 00:32:56.828
amplified in lung cancer. And we didn't know much about

562
00:32:56.888 --> 00:32:58.648
NDK2 except for

563
00:32:59.828 --> 00:33:03.628
its role in antioxidant generation, and it was thought that the

564
00:33:03.728 --> 00:33:07.228
major function of mitochondrial NADPH is to

565
00:33:07.288 --> 00:33:07.988
recycle

566
00:33:09.088 --> 00:33:13.028
glutathione to inhibit ROS, given that mitochondria is a

567
00:33:13.128 --> 00:33:16.428
major site of ROS. However, given

568
00:33:16.468 --> 00:33:20.328
its association with cancer and of course, these are reducing

569
00:33:20.368 --> 00:33:24.248
cofactors that they are important, we wanted to know more if there's

570
00:33:24.328 --> 00:33:28.208
more functions of mitochondrial NADPH beyond

571
00:33:28.288 --> 00:33:28.688
ROS.

572
00:33:29.668 --> 00:33:33.188
So we knocked out NDK2 in a variety of different

573
00:33:33.228 --> 00:33:36.958
proliferating cells and cancer cells, including lung cancer cells,

574
00:33:37.348 --> 00:33:41.248
and it was very apparent that NDK2 loss has a strong

575
00:33:41.308 --> 00:33:44.868
effect on cell growth and proliferation, shown here

576
00:33:46.148 --> 00:33:50.028
with these black marks. And if we take cancer

577
00:33:50.068 --> 00:33:53.848
cells and put them in tumors, as shown in here in this A549 lung

578
00:33:53.908 --> 00:33:57.608
cancer tumors, we see that NDK2 loss has a strong and

579
00:33:57.668 --> 00:34:00.068
drastic defect also on tumor growth.

580
00:34:00.908 --> 00:34:04.828
Perhaps it's not very surprising that when you knock out a key metabolic

581
00:34:04.888 --> 00:34:08.728
enzyme that you reduce cell fitness, but we're

582
00:34:08.808 --> 00:34:12.649
very curious if there were certain metabolic dependencies of mitochondrial

583
00:34:12.768 --> 00:34:15.688
NADPH. So we gave cells a variety of

584
00:34:16.468 --> 00:34:20.388
metabolites, including antioxidants, nucleotides,

585
00:34:20.488 --> 00:34:21.388
fatty acids,

586
00:34:22.649 --> 00:34:26.048
and amino acids. And what we observed was that loss of

587
00:34:26.089 --> 00:34:29.488
NDK2 was completely restored by giving

588
00:34:29.508 --> 00:34:33.188
non-essential amino acids, and we have about seven of these non-essential

589
00:34:33.248 --> 00:34:36.748
amino acids. And what was really striking was that in

590
00:34:36.768 --> 00:34:40.468
particular, proline was really key for proliferating

591
00:34:40.928 --> 00:34:44.488
NDK2 knockout cells. So proline alone was able to

592
00:34:44.527 --> 00:34:47.669
restore cell proliferation in these proline

593
00:34:47.688 --> 00:34:50.548
auxotroph NDK2 knockout cells.

594
00:34:51.268 --> 00:34:53.408
So we asked the question, why proline?

595
00:34:54.048 --> 00:34:56.109
So proline metabolism is

596
00:34:56.988 --> 00:34:59.828
quite easy compared to any other metabolic pathways.

597
00:35:00.308 --> 00:35:03.868
We can generate proline in the mitochondria through conversion from

598
00:35:03.908 --> 00:35:07.688
glutamate into glutamine semialdehyde, which is then cyclized to

599
00:35:07.768 --> 00:35:11.428
P5C, and it's reduced to proline. And as you might

600
00:35:11.488 --> 00:35:14.088
appreciate in these cofactors here shown in violet,

601
00:35:15.248 --> 00:35:18.928
NADPH is one of the cofactors that seems to be required for proline

602
00:35:18.968 --> 00:35:22.448
metabolism. So we perform metabolic tracing, this case with

603
00:35:22.488 --> 00:35:25.928
glutamine, to look at generation of newly synthesized proline.

604
00:35:26.568 --> 00:35:30.368
And what was one of the most black and white results that we

605
00:35:30.428 --> 00:35:33.718
have seen, at least in my lab, was that loss of NDK2

606
00:35:34.088 --> 00:35:37.928
completely disrupted proline biosynthesis,

607
00:35:38.968 --> 00:35:42.048
indicating that NDK2 is essential for proline

608
00:35:42.068 --> 00:35:45.968
generation. And this gave us also a little bit of closure to explain

609
00:35:46.208 --> 00:35:49.778
why these cells can't grow without proline, and the reason is that,

610
00:35:50.148 --> 00:35:51.528
well, they cannot make proline.

611
00:35:52.368 --> 00:35:56.168
So basically, I identified that a key role of mitochondrial

612
00:35:56.268 --> 00:36:00.128
NADPH is to generate proline to sustain cell growth and

613
00:36:00.148 --> 00:36:00.928
proliferation.

614
00:36:02.368 --> 00:36:06.028
However, we were very curious beyond proline and beyond ROS, whether

615
00:36:06.068 --> 00:36:09.648
mitochondrial NADPH could also have other functions in the

616
00:36:09.688 --> 00:36:13.308
cells. So as many people in this audience and in

617
00:36:13.318 --> 00:36:17.068
metabolism do, we went back and performed a steady-state metabolomics

618
00:36:17.128 --> 00:36:19.398
experiment in isogenic cell lines.

619
00:36:19.928 --> 00:36:23.168
And in addition to proline, we also observed that several

620
00:36:23.178 --> 00:36:26.608
metabolites in the TCA cycle, including citrate,

621
00:36:26.648 --> 00:36:30.508
isocitrate, fumarate, were also reduced in

622
00:36:30.608 --> 00:36:34.480
NDK2 knockout cells.To us, this was a little

623
00:36:34.540 --> 00:36:38.440
bit of a surprising result, and that's because we know that NADPH

624
00:36:38.480 --> 00:36:41.850
supports many processes, especially anabolic processes and

625
00:36:41.900 --> 00:36:44.120
antioxidant processes. However,

626
00:36:44.660 --> 00:36:48.460
there's no connection between NADPH

627
00:36:48.580 --> 00:36:52.500
and TCA cycle, as TCA cycles runs primarily on

628
00:36:52.700 --> 00:36:53.120
NAD.

629
00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:57.960
So we went deeper into why NADK2 and how NADK2 might

630
00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:00.980
affect TCA cycle. So in this case, we performed pyruvate

631
00:37:01.040 --> 00:37:04.520
tracing. So pyruvate is the end stage of

632
00:37:04.560 --> 00:37:06.840
glycolysis, which enters the TCA cycle.

633
00:37:06.980 --> 00:37:10.660
It's decarboxylated or oxidized by an enzyme called PDH

634
00:37:11.320 --> 00:37:14.600
and generates acetyl-CoA, which then is conjugated to

635
00:37:14.640 --> 00:37:18.550
oxaloacetate to generate citrate that jumpstart the TCA cycle.

636
00:37:19.240 --> 00:37:23.160
So in an isogenic setting of NADK2 wild type and knockout

637
00:37:23.240 --> 00:37:27.220
cells, either in the presence or absence of proline, as we know, because

638
00:37:27.260 --> 00:37:30.940
proline is one of the major functions of mitochondrial NADPH,

639
00:37:31.840 --> 00:37:35.820
we assess the TCA cycle, and interestingly, we observe that various

640
00:37:35.860 --> 00:37:39.820
metabolites in the TCA cycle, where the fractional abundance of them were

641
00:37:39.860 --> 00:37:43.680
reduced in NADK2 knockout cells. However, this was not dependent

642
00:37:43.720 --> 00:37:47.400
on proline, indicating that mitochondrial NADPH

643
00:37:47.520 --> 00:37:51.220
regulates TCA cycle independently of proline.

644
00:37:52.520 --> 00:37:56.140
And given that the first metabolite citrate was reduced, we were

645
00:37:56.200 --> 00:37:59.970
curious whether the step of the regulation might be upstream and

646
00:37:59.980 --> 00:38:02.360
perhaps at the pyruvate dehydrogenase step.

647
00:38:02.900 --> 00:38:06.560
So for this, we did a time course experiment with pyruvate tracing and looked at

648
00:38:06.580 --> 00:38:10.480
acetyl-CoA production. And interestingly, we observed a reduction

649
00:38:10.520 --> 00:38:14.480
in acetyl-CoA levels in every time point in response to NADK2

650
00:38:14.490 --> 00:38:18.480
loss, indicating that we have an impairment in pyruvate

651
00:38:18.520 --> 00:38:21.860
oxidation. We did many experiments, including in vitro

652
00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:26.120
assays of PDH activity, as well as radioactive

653
00:38:26.580 --> 00:38:30.140
assays when we would label with radioactive

654
00:38:30.260 --> 00:38:33.150
pyruvate and measure the captured CO2 via

655
00:38:33.540 --> 00:38:37.340
radioactivity. Again, another surrogate assay for PDH

656
00:38:37.360 --> 00:38:41.270
activity. And again, we observe a reduction in

657
00:38:41.280 --> 00:38:44.820
pyruvate oxidation, indicating that NADK2 loss

658
00:38:44.860 --> 00:38:47.800
somehow affects the pyruvate dehydrogenase step.

659
00:38:48.860 --> 00:38:51.420
But how does it affect? So what is PDH?

660
00:38:51.460 --> 00:38:55.360
So PDH or pyruvate dehydrogenase is a really critical enzyme

661
00:38:55.400 --> 00:38:57.180
in the mitochondria. It's a complex that

662
00:38:58.420 --> 00:39:02.220
has three subunits, E1, E2, and E3, and it's important because it's the

663
00:39:02.280 --> 00:39:06.140
link between glycolysis and TCA. So basically, it's the entry

664
00:39:06.260 --> 00:39:10.120
point of pyruvate to generate energy in the TCA cycle.

665
00:39:10.660 --> 00:39:13.790
It's a highly regulated enzyme. It's regulated by cofactor

666
00:39:13.840 --> 00:39:17.560
availability. It's regulated by phosphorylation events.

667
00:39:17.600 --> 00:39:21.220
But it's also regulated by more exotic post-translational

668
00:39:21.240 --> 00:39:24.900
modification, and one of these post-translational modification is called

669
00:39:24.940 --> 00:39:28.820
lipoylation. So lipoylation is the C8 group or

670
00:39:28.880 --> 00:39:32.640
a lipid group that is attaching to the E2 subunit of PDH,

671
00:39:32.960 --> 00:39:36.640
and basically, it acts as a prostate group and

672
00:39:36.700 --> 00:39:39.020
facilitates substrate channeling.

673
00:39:39.100 --> 00:39:42.800
And it's really critical for optimal enzyme activity.

674
00:39:43.380 --> 00:39:47.240
So we looked at many functions and many regulatory modes of PDH,

675
00:39:47.760 --> 00:39:51.260
and what was very surprising was that loss of

676
00:39:51.380 --> 00:39:54.520
NADK2 had an effect on PDH

677
00:39:54.540 --> 00:39:58.440
lipoylation. So here, this is an immunoblot of endogenous

678
00:39:58.540 --> 00:40:01.940
DLAT or the E2 subunit. And as you might

679
00:40:01.980 --> 00:40:05.720
appreciate, loss of NADK2 shows a reduction in lipoic

680
00:40:05.780 --> 00:40:09.760
acid, and when we give back NADK2, we can restore

681
00:40:09.780 --> 00:40:12.680
lipoic acid. So this is an antibody-based assay.

682
00:40:12.960 --> 00:40:16.460
However, we've done also mass spectrometry to

683
00:40:16.500 --> 00:40:19.300
define the sites that are lipoylated.

684
00:40:20.900 --> 00:40:24.420
So protein lipoylation, as I mentioned, it's a rare

685
00:40:24.700 --> 00:40:26.300
post-translational modification.

686
00:40:26.340 --> 00:40:30.320
In fact, it's so rare that it only happens, or to date, it's only found in

687
00:40:30.400 --> 00:40:34.080
five proteins, and these five proteins are all in the mitochondria

688
00:40:34.580 --> 00:40:36.740
and are present in four complexes.

689
00:40:37.100 --> 00:40:39.640
One of them is DLAT in the PDH complex.

690
00:40:40.220 --> 00:40:43.860
OGDH complex also has DLST. Both of these

691
00:40:44.160 --> 00:40:48.080
fuel the TCA cycle. But there's also lipoylated components

692
00:40:48.120 --> 00:40:52.100
that are found in glycine cleavage system as well as

693
00:40:52.200 --> 00:40:54.080
BCKDH in the breast chain

694
00:40:55.520 --> 00:40:59.490
complex. So we were curious whether NADK2 affects general

695
00:40:59.580 --> 00:41:03.360
protein lipoylation or whether there's something specific about PDH.

696
00:41:03.800 --> 00:41:07.680
So in order to address this question, we expressed these various components

697
00:41:07.720 --> 00:41:11.540
that are known to be lipoylated, either in wild type or NADK2 knockout

698
00:41:11.620 --> 00:41:15.600
cells. And in general, we observed that there is a reduction

699
00:41:15.640 --> 00:41:16.200
in lipoic

700
00:41:17.160 --> 00:41:21.020
acid in all of these proteins, indicating that NADK2

701
00:41:21.080 --> 00:41:23.920
loss affects general protein lipoylation.

702
00:41:25.280 --> 00:41:27.280
Given that enzymes might

703
00:41:28.120 --> 00:41:29.560
either act as scaffolding,

704
00:41:31.160 --> 00:41:33.140
so we were curious whether

705
00:41:34.020 --> 00:41:37.480
the activity of NADK2 was critical for this.

706
00:41:37.540 --> 00:41:41.060
And in order to answer that question, so again, we used an isogenic

707
00:41:41.100 --> 00:41:44.860
system of NADK2 knockout cells, where we either added

708
00:41:44.900 --> 00:41:47.320
back active NADK2 or

709
00:41:47.360 --> 00:41:51.000
kinase-inactive NADK2, or we

710
00:41:51.040 --> 00:41:54.950
engineered cytosolic NADK with a mitochondrial targeting

711
00:41:55.900 --> 00:41:59.680
sequence to edit in the mitochondria, and now we're restoring

712
00:41:59.740 --> 00:42:03.240
mitochondrial NADPH. Interestingly, we

713
00:42:03.280 --> 00:42:06.860
observed that whenever we have mitochondrial NADPH, either with

714
00:42:06.960 --> 00:42:10.820
active NADK2 or with cytosolic NADK that

715
00:42:10.860 --> 00:42:14.800
is in the mitochondria, we see that there is restoration of lipoic acid,

716
00:42:15.160 --> 00:42:18.760
indicating that there's actually NADPH in the mitochondria, not just

717
00:42:18.880 --> 00:42:21.580
NADK2, that matters for lipoylation.

718
00:42:22.860 --> 00:42:26.200
So what impacts protein lipoylation by

719
00:42:26.300 --> 00:42:30.180
NADK2? So when we read the literature, we found that a

720
00:42:30.320 --> 00:42:34.260
key pathway that determines protein lipoylation is mitochondrial fatty

721
00:42:34.320 --> 00:42:35.460
acid biosynthesis.

722
00:42:36.360 --> 00:42:39.996
SoThis has remained an obscure pathway,

723
00:42:40.316 --> 00:42:43.836
and I'm sure that a lot of you have heard about the cytosolic fatty acid

724
00:42:43.876 --> 00:42:47.476
biosynthesis, which is a critical process for generation of fatty

725
00:42:47.536 --> 00:42:51.256
acids, for energy generation, for membrane generation in the

726
00:42:51.296 --> 00:42:55.276
cells. However, mitochondria has a specialized

727
00:42:55.296 --> 00:42:59.136
fatty acid synthesis called mitochondrial fatty acid biosynthesis that

728
00:42:59.196 --> 00:43:03.096
actually, it's not really linked for energy generation or for

729
00:43:03.276 --> 00:43:06.916
membrane or cardiolipin, even though people thought that it could be important for

730
00:43:06.996 --> 00:43:10.556
cardiolipin synthesis. But it's very tightly

731
00:43:10.656 --> 00:43:13.956
coupled to the mitochondria function and to oxidative

732
00:43:14.476 --> 00:43:15.236
metabolism.

733
00:43:16.056 --> 00:43:19.716
However, this pathway has remained obscure, and what we know

734
00:43:19.816 --> 00:43:23.426
about this pathway has been primarily coming from the work from

735
00:43:23.516 --> 00:43:27.396
bacteria or genetics from yeast. And the reason

736
00:43:27.456 --> 00:43:30.936
that we haven't quite measured this pathway in mammalian cells

737
00:43:31.696 --> 00:43:34.976
is because of the chemistry. So fatty acids in the

738
00:43:35.016 --> 00:43:38.656
mitochondria are elongated on top of

739
00:43:38.716 --> 00:43:41.556
another protein called the acyl carrier protein.

740
00:43:41.995 --> 00:43:45.916
So basically, you have the covalent modification of these fatty acids that

741
00:43:45.956 --> 00:43:48.656
are further elongated on top of ACP.

742
00:43:49.076 --> 00:43:52.736
So a general method like metabolomics or lipidomics would not

743
00:43:52.796 --> 00:43:55.776
reveal this fatty acid that are attached to ACP.

744
00:43:56.356 --> 00:44:00.016
However, work from bacteria has suggested that some of this enzyme, for example,

745
00:44:00.116 --> 00:44:02.476
MeCCR, in this pathway, can use NADPH.

746
00:44:03.056 --> 00:44:06.996
So we were, again, very curious whether mitochondrial NADPH can

747
00:44:07.076 --> 00:44:09.156
supply mitochondrial fatty acid synthesis.

748
00:44:09.536 --> 00:44:13.256
However, no one had measured this before in mammalian cells.

749
00:44:14.736 --> 00:44:18.596
We were very inspired by work from Doug Allen at the

750
00:44:18.656 --> 00:44:22.516
University of Missouri, who had measured mitochondrial fatty

751
00:44:22.596 --> 00:44:26.406
acid in plants, and in particular in these

752
00:44:26.436 --> 00:44:28.476
Camelina plants in oilseed crops.

753
00:44:28.536 --> 00:44:32.296
So Doug had collected a lot of crop, and

754
00:44:34.076 --> 00:44:37.996
their lab basically used an endopeptidase which would

755
00:44:38.096 --> 00:44:39.086
release these

756
00:44:40.356 --> 00:44:43.076
acyl chains from the acyl carrier protein.

757
00:44:43.256 --> 00:44:47.236
So now we can detect the acyl chains

758
00:44:47.316 --> 00:44:47.856
using

759
00:44:48.776 --> 00:44:50.696
classical metabolomics techniques.

760
00:44:51.296 --> 00:44:55.156
So, I wrote to Doug, and we started a collaboration with

761
00:44:55.216 --> 00:44:58.896
him, and he was very, very generous and sent us all the standards

762
00:44:58.996 --> 00:44:59.836
for ACP.

763
00:45:00.656 --> 00:45:03.636
And we tried to see if we can get it to work in mammalian cells.

764
00:45:04.236 --> 00:45:06.656
So first, to set the system, we use

765
00:45:07.756 --> 00:45:11.376
MeCCR wild-type or knockouts. So MeCCR is one of the enzyme in the mitochondrial

766
00:45:11.436 --> 00:45:13.376
fatty acid biosynthesis. And MeCCR loss,

767
00:45:14.296 --> 00:45:17.196
