00:57:16.376 --> 00:57:19.566
And then the other one is actually going to harken back to some whole body

978
00:57:19.606 --> 00:57:23.526
metabolism. Josh introduced this a bit, but I want to share with you a little work

979
00:57:23.566 --> 00:57:27.376
we've been doing to try to understand some of the links between

980
00:57:27.406 --> 00:57:28.795
pancreas cancer and

981
00:57:29.906 --> 00:57:30.566
tissue wasting.

982
00:57:31.406 --> 00:57:35.396
Okay. Now, if we just think about here's methods that are used in

983
00:57:35.406 --> 00:57:39.045
the clinic to look at differences in metabolism in patients.

984
00:57:39.106 --> 00:57:42.946
And I like to point out that most people are familiar with FDG-PET, but

985
00:57:42.986 --> 00:57:46.926
this is not the only PET modality that exists in patients to looks

986
00:57:46.986 --> 00:57:49.786
at metabolism. We have here Fluciclovine PET.

987
00:57:49.826 --> 00:57:51.746
This is something to do with amino acid uptake.

988
00:57:51.866 --> 00:57:55.276
FLT PET is basically a BRDU assay or

989
00:57:55.306 --> 00:57:59.206
thymidine uptake. And I point these out not because I'm

990
00:57:59.226 --> 00:58:02.866
going to spend a lot of time about various PET modalities, but to point out that I

991
00:58:02.886 --> 00:58:05.826
think many people know that not all tumors are PET positive.

992
00:58:06.346 --> 00:58:10.286
Well, not all tumors are Fluciclovine PET positive or FLT PET positive.

993
00:58:10.346 --> 00:58:13.926
That is, each different cancer type seems to have its own

994
00:58:13.936 --> 00:58:17.866
spectrum of what various PET tracers it takes up, which

995
00:58:17.946 --> 00:58:21.866
I think at some deep level tells us something about the metabolism of the tumors.

996
00:58:21.966 --> 00:58:25.946
I think it says that not all cancers do the same metabolism, and

997
00:58:26.006 --> 00:58:29.726
that has led us as well as many other groups to want to ask the question, well, if

998
00:58:29.806 --> 00:58:33.126
not all cancers do the same metabolism, what determines the

999
00:58:33.146 --> 00:58:35.546
metabolism that individual cancers do?

1000
00:58:36.526 --> 00:58:39.006
And I'm going to summarize work here from many groups.

1001
00:58:40.006 --> 00:58:41.926
It really comes down to three factors.

1002
00:58:42.366 --> 00:58:46.106
Initially, the field of cancer metabolism, the resurgence and

1003
00:58:46.166 --> 00:58:50.026
interest in this field came from the observation that various genetic

1004
00:58:50.046 --> 00:58:53.326
mutations can affect metabolism, and that's absolutely true.

1005
00:58:53.346 --> 00:58:57.286
But I think increasingly what we've realized from work by

1006
00:58:57.326 --> 00:59:01.246
Josh, but also many others as well, that where cancer

1007
00:59:01.286 --> 00:59:04.686
comes from also can affect the various metabolic phenotypes of

1008
00:59:06.306 --> 00:59:09.266
cancer cells. And of course, where the

1009
00:59:10.506 --> 00:59:14.166
tissue or where the cancer is located, that is the nutrients in the environment,

1010
00:59:14.806 --> 00:59:18.686
seems to have a quite important effect on the metabolism

1011
00:59:18.726 --> 00:59:22.616
that cancers do. And at some level, I think this makes some sense because

1012
00:59:22.906 --> 00:59:25.846
these are sort of cell intrinsic things that have to do with the tumor.

1013
00:59:25.946 --> 00:59:29.485
That is, these define the network of what metabolism

1014
00:59:29.545 --> 00:59:33.486
can actually accomplish. But if you take any network and you put

1015
00:59:33.506 --> 00:59:37.026
it in a situation where nutrients are infinitely abundant,

1016
00:59:37.446 --> 00:59:39.426
well, that network is going to look very flexible.

1017
00:59:39.446 --> 00:59:43.406
And the reality is that real cancers arise in tissues where not

1018
00:59:43.446 --> 00:59:47.246
all nutrients are available. And so that has led at least

1019
00:59:47.346 --> 00:59:51.066
us, but many others as well, to really focus on this notion that

1020
00:59:51.126 --> 00:59:55.006
maybe it's the constraints placed by nutrients in the environment on the

1021
00:59:55.026 --> 00:59:58.386
cell-intrinsic networks that exist within individual cancer

1022
00:59:58.426 --> 01:00:02.356
cells that ultimately are creating these bottlenecks that determine what

1023
01:00:02.386 --> 01:00:06.366
different cancers can do, and ultimately may reflect why it is

1024
01:00:06.426 --> 01:00:10.186
that you see different metabolic phenotypes across different cancers, as well

1025
01:00:10.246 --> 01:00:14.186
as different dependencies across different cancers as well.

1026
01:00:14.206 --> 01:00:17.946
And so for the last several years, my group has been very interested in trying to

1027
01:00:18.026 --> 01:00:21.766
better understand what nutrients are actually in the environment, and this is

1028
01:00:21.786 --> 01:00:25.566
where some of the techniques that Josh introduced earlier can become very useful.

1029
01:00:25.966 --> 01:00:29.206
Things like mass spectrometry to measure nutrient levels.

1030
01:00:29.266 --> 01:00:33.086
And we and others in the field have now done this across many different

1031
01:00:33.106 --> 01:00:37.046
tumor types. And because a lot of this is published, I'm just going to show you one

1032
01:00:37.086 --> 01:00:40.826
experiment. This was done by Keene Abbott, a former graduate

1033
01:00:40.886 --> 01:00:44.276
student in the lab. It was published earlier this year.

1034
01:00:44.846 --> 01:00:48.826
But it's sort of illustrative what we and I think others in the field

1035
01:00:48.886 --> 01:00:52.286
have been finding is we've been asking, well, what nutrients are actually

1036
01:00:52.346 --> 01:00:56.286
found in various locations, in this case within a mouse, but it's also true

1037
01:00:56.346 --> 01:01:00.186
within patients. And I think this is just a principal component plot that is a

1038
01:01:00.226 --> 01:01:03.826
way to sort of collapse all of the quantitative mass spectrometry

1039
01:01:04.326 --> 01:01:06.946
data that we've collected onto a single 2D plot.

1040
01:01:07.346 --> 01:01:09.346
And effectively, what we all know that

1041
01:01:10.306 --> 01:01:14.132
what weGive cells in standard tissue culture is not

1042
01:01:14.142 --> 01:01:15.481
physiological.

1043
01:01:16.282 --> 01:01:19.882
But this actually points out, well, this is the nutrient environment of blood.

1044
01:01:19.922 --> 01:01:23.762
This is the nutrient environment of all the various tissue sites that Keane could

1045
01:01:23.802 --> 01:01:27.772
take out of a mouse. And what you can see here is that, well, blood is different

1046
01:01:27.802 --> 01:01:31.732
than tissue culture, not shown, but blood is also different from what's in

1047
01:01:31.762 --> 01:01:35.752
various tissues. And I think increasingly what I at least find striking

1048
01:01:35.782 --> 01:01:38.952
is that each tissue is also different from each other.

1049
01:01:38.962 --> 01:01:42.822
Now, I'm not going to show you all the data for this, but it turns out if you

1050
01:01:42.862 --> 01:01:46.102
take different strains of mice, this largely holds.

1051
01:01:46.152 --> 01:01:50.122
And so I think it's really each of our tissues, something about those tissues

1052
01:01:50.162 --> 01:01:53.742
in ways that we do not understand seems to have a

1053
01:01:53.802 --> 01:01:57.591
distinct nutrient environment that is defining of that

1054
01:01:57.642 --> 01:02:01.231
tissue. And I think in terms of thinking about cancer, this matters

1055
01:02:01.722 --> 01:02:05.622
because if we simply reformulate media conditions to match what's

1056
01:02:05.662 --> 01:02:09.502
found in different tissues, it also matters for how well cancers

1057
01:02:09.522 --> 01:02:12.442
can grow. Now again, this is all published data, so I'm just going to

1058
01:02:12.922 --> 01:02:15.002
summarize the findings from these things.

1059
01:02:15.062 --> 01:02:18.822
But effectively, if we take various, these are from pancreatic cancer, either

1060
01:02:18.862 --> 01:02:22.412
primary tumors or metastasis, and we try to grow them in blood-like conditions,

1061
01:02:22.842 --> 01:02:26.802
well, they grow quite well. They actually grow quite similarly to what we see in

1062
01:02:27.902 --> 01:02:31.362
tissue culture. But if we go to the more restricted conditions that we found in

1063
01:02:31.422 --> 01:02:35.082
various tissues, they have clear preferences for nutrient environments, in this

1064
01:02:35.122 --> 01:02:38.422
case, the nutrient environment found in the pancreas.

1065
01:02:38.502 --> 01:02:41.772
And in that same paper, that was work of Charanu Sivananthan.

1066
01:02:41.822 --> 01:02:45.342
In the same paper that I alluded to earlier that Keane Abbott published,

1067
01:02:45.782 --> 01:02:49.362
he also did a lot of work to try to dissect, well, what's actually

1068
01:02:49.402 --> 01:02:52.902
driving this? And effectively the argument is that it's actually

1069
01:02:53.002 --> 01:02:56.442
multiple nutrients cooperating within those environments that are actually

1070
01:02:56.502 --> 01:02:59.742
driving this preference to grow in different locations.

1071
01:03:00.642 --> 01:03:04.442
Now, what I want to focus on here in terms of today's talk, though, is that while

1072
01:03:04.502 --> 01:03:08.452
that's all well and good, but can we actually use this to learn something about

1073
01:03:08.482 --> 01:03:11.542
metabolic limitations within cancer?

1074
01:03:12.122 --> 01:03:15.982
And so one approach that we had to do that is we said, well, if it's true that

1075
01:03:16.022 --> 01:03:18.682
nutrients vary in different tissues across the body,

1076
01:03:19.501 --> 01:03:22.982
well, a good question to ask is, well, what actually is

1077
01:03:23.042 --> 01:03:26.802
responsible for this variance? That is, what's actually different

1078
01:03:26.842 --> 01:03:29.062
across each of these different sites?

1079
01:03:29.532 --> 01:03:33.342
And so one can use various math things and other ways to

1080
01:03:33.362 --> 01:03:37.222
look at this. I don't want to get into the details of that, but one thing

1081
01:03:37.262 --> 01:03:41.042
that really stands out that is characteristic of each tissue is that

1082
01:03:41.082 --> 01:03:44.802
each tissue is very different in terms of its nucleotide and nucleotide

1083
01:03:44.922 --> 01:03:48.802
precursor availability. That is, some

1084
01:03:48.862 --> 01:03:51.482
tissues might be high in salvageable purines.

1085
01:03:51.542 --> 01:03:54.162
Some tissues might be high in salvageable pyrimidines.

1086
01:03:54.582 --> 01:03:57.102
Some might have thymidine, some might have cytosine, et cetera.

1087
01:03:57.702 --> 01:04:01.322
And this to us was very striking for a variety of reasons.

1088
01:04:01.402 --> 01:04:05.082
But to study this, we needed to come up with a system to actually model it.

1089
01:04:05.522 --> 01:04:09.162
And the way we decided to do this was actually to use acute

1090
01:04:09.222 --> 01:04:13.011
lymphoblastic leukemia. And we did this for a couple reasons.

1091
01:04:13.242 --> 01:04:16.722
One is because with the help of Jana Pickman, who's a pediatric

1092
01:04:16.762 --> 01:04:20.262
oncologist at Dana-Farber, she had access to bone marrow

1093
01:04:20.302 --> 01:04:24.162
plasma from a large number of kids that happened to have

1094
01:04:24.242 --> 01:04:28.042
