1096
01:04:31.462 --> 01:04:34.762
quantitative mass spec on part of our effort to try to understand different

1097
01:04:34.802 --> 01:04:36.442
nutrient environments across tissue.

1098
01:04:37.022 --> 01:04:40.482
I will say the one nutrient environment, at least to the extent bone marrow plasma,

1099
01:04:40.542 --> 01:04:44.342
is reflective of bone marrow, and that's a debate we could have, but that

1100
01:04:44.382 --> 01:04:47.242
looks a lot like plasma. So that's one good thing.

1101
01:04:47.682 --> 01:04:51.222
And the other thing is that this is acute lymphoblastic leukemia.

1102
01:04:51.322 --> 01:04:54.832
So it grows in the bone marrow, it grows in the blood, so this is a physiological

1103
01:04:54.862 --> 01:04:58.812
environment for this. Now, it turns out you do this

1104
01:04:58.862 --> 01:05:02.402
in humans, we could also do it in a mouse model of Philadelphia-positive

1105
01:05:02.522 --> 01:05:05.302
B-ALL. This is a mouse model we got from Mike Hemann's lab.

1106
01:05:05.642 --> 01:05:09.022
He didn't originally make it. It was originally made by Chuck Sherr many, many

1107
01:05:09.102 --> 01:05:11.362
years ago. It's basically BCR-ABL

1108
01:05:12.922 --> 01:05:15.862
expressed on a, I think it's P19 background.

1109
01:05:16.302 --> 01:05:19.982
These mice get B-ALL, and it's a very specific model of

1110
01:05:20.022 --> 01:05:23.782
B-ALL. But regardless, if we simply ask what's

1111
01:05:23.791 --> 01:05:27.602
different between the blood of either humans or mice that

1112
01:05:27.642 --> 01:05:31.072
have lymphoblastic leukemia versus healthy

1113
01:05:31.162 --> 01:05:35.042
controls, well, again, it's nucleotides

1114
01:05:35.062 --> 01:05:38.822
that really stand out. And so we decided, well, maybe

1115
01:05:38.942 --> 01:05:42.842
we could actually leverage this then as a system to try to

1116
01:05:42.902 --> 01:05:46.782
understand how it is that this variation in nucleotide levels

1117
01:05:46.822 --> 01:05:49.692
might actually matter. Now, the way we did this

1118
01:05:49.822 --> 01:05:53.042
is Rayan El-Bashir, a

1119
01:05:53.122 --> 01:05:56.722
soon-to-be graduated PhD student from my lab,

1120
01:05:57.562 --> 01:06:00.642
worked with Keane initially, although did most of this work on her own, where she

