01:06:07.922 --> 01:06:11.802
study what actually might matter between sort of the way we

1124
01:06:11.862 --> 01:06:15.542
standardly grow cells or not. Now, we decided to do this in

1125
01:06:15.582 --> 01:06:17.842
mouse. You could criticize us for doing it in mouse.

1126
01:06:17.902 --> 01:06:21.202
I know that's kind of out of fashion right now, but I will tell you the reason we

1127
01:06:21.222 --> 01:06:24.282
did it in mouse, because we wanted to be able to go back into the mouse after we

1128
01:06:24.982 --> 01:06:27.082
manipulated these things and look at it.

1129
01:06:27.142 --> 01:06:30.812
So there are some interesting mouse-human differences if people want to talk about

1130
01:06:30.842 --> 01:06:34.562
that. But regardless, I think we learned something here ultimately

1131
01:06:34.662 --> 01:06:38.582
that I think does apply to humans, even if the exact details of what we found

1132
01:06:39.362 --> 01:06:43.322
may be mouse specific. But regardless, this is just to point out that we can

1133
01:06:43.382 --> 01:06:46.842
take B-ALL cells, and if we grow them in media that's formulated,

1134
01:06:46.982 --> 01:06:50.562
what Rayan called MPM for mouse plasma-like media,

1135
01:06:51.022 --> 01:06:53.482
it grows almost as well as it does in RPMI.

1136
01:06:53.822 --> 01:06:56.962
But if you just do metabolomics and you just ask what's different?

1137
01:06:57.172 --> 01:06:58.982
Again, what's different is nucleotides.

1138
01:06:59.042 --> 01:07:02.522
Really underscoring that nucleotide metabolism

1139
01:07:02.642 --> 01:07:04.962
is affected by these different

1140
01:07:05.002 --> 01:07:08.782
environments.So what Rayann wanted to do, somewhat

1141
01:07:08.862 --> 01:07:12.802
inspired by Gertha's work, is actually use

1142
01:07:12.842 --> 01:07:16.832
tracing. And so from a methods workshop, this is basically using isotope

1143
01:07:16.922 --> 01:07:20.742
tracing. The way we did this for the aficionados out there is we basically

1144
01:07:20.782 --> 01:07:24.592
used glutamine tracing, which labels bases only, coupled

1145
01:07:24.622 --> 01:07:28.272
with glucose tracing. So glucose tracing, if it labels just the five

1146
01:07:28.322 --> 01:07:32.212
carbon ribose, you can largely tell what's salvaged because

1147
01:07:32.242 --> 01:07:34.622
that has to be salvaged of a preformed base.

1148
01:07:35.502 --> 01:07:37.982
Or you can see glucose also contribute

1149
01:07:37.992 --> 01:07:41.772
to the bases as well. But

1150
01:07:41.842 --> 01:07:45.622
regardless, we could use the various isotopomer distributions and estimate

1151
01:07:45.682 --> 01:07:49.502
it from those, how much of the nucleotide pools growing in

1152
01:07:49.582 --> 01:07:53.572
RPMI versus mouse plasma-like media conditions were

1153
01:07:53.602 --> 01:07:57.162
coming from different sources, and perhaps not surprisingly, because your

1154
01:07:57.242 --> 01:08:00.242
RPMI has absolutely no nucleotides in it.

1155
01:08:00.562 --> 01:08:03.912
It's all from de novo synthesis. Whereas under salvage conditions,

1156
01:08:04.002 --> 01:08:05.872
well, they salvage the nucleotides.

1157
01:08:06.342 --> 01:08:09.482
Now, many people say, "Well, of course, we've known that for a long time.

1158
01:08:09.542 --> 01:08:11.262
It's expensive to make nucleotides.

1159
01:08:11.362 --> 01:08:15.242
If you need nucleotides, well, you'll salvage them if you make them

1160
01:08:15.322 --> 01:08:18.963
available." But where this gets interesting here is as follows, and that's, well,

1161
01:08:19.242 --> 01:08:21.282
what if you add nucleotides to RPMI?

1162
01:08:21.322 --> 01:08:23.623
It makes zero difference on how well the cells grow.

1163
01:08:24.142 --> 01:08:28.132
But if you take the nucleotides away from the mouse plasma-like media, well,

1164
01:08:28.163 --> 01:08:31.963
now the cells don't grow as well, which means they care about those

1165
01:08:32.003 --> 01:08:35.602
nucleotides. And in fact, if you knock out salvage enzymes

1166
01:08:35.663 --> 01:08:39.322
versus synthesis enzymes, you actually learn something even more

1167
01:08:39.362 --> 01:08:43.163
interesting. So if you look here at this experiment, if we knock out

1168
01:08:43.222 --> 01:08:46.873
synthesis enzymes, well, if you grow cells in RPMI, these two gray bars right

1169
01:08:46.902 --> 01:08:50.352
here, what you see is, of course, they don't grow without synthesis enzymes, and

1170
01:08:50.362 --> 01:08:52.882
they don't care about salvage. This is a salvage knockout.

1171
01:08:53.282 --> 01:08:56.862
But you notice here, just like you might have predicted from there, you care about

1172
01:08:56.963 --> 01:09:00.562
salvage in the MPM condition, but you also still care

1173
01:09:00.663 --> 01:09:04.302
about synthesis. And we found this a little bit weird

1174
01:09:04.802 --> 01:09:08.142
because this is not a nutrient-deprived condition.

1175
01:09:08.623 --> 01:09:11.562
Yes, it's nutrient different. It's not what's in RPMI.

1176
01:09:12.862 --> 01:09:16.482
It's different, but not necessarily

1177
01:09:16.522 --> 01:09:20.422
nutrient deprived, which really then raised the question, well, why is it

1178
01:09:20.482 --> 01:09:24.382
that nucleotide synthesis is specifically constrained in these plasma-like

1179
01:09:24.442 --> 01:09:27.722
conditions but not constrained in RPMI?

1180
01:09:28.382 --> 01:09:32.062
And so Rayann considered all the various possibilities, and I'll just go right to

1181
01:09:32.102 --> 01:09:34.463
the experiment here that says exactly what's going on.

1182
01:09:34.543 --> 01:09:38.262
So this is just metabolomics, and there's three metabolites that

1183
01:09:38.342 --> 01:09:42.182
stand out like a sore thumb. So you basically only see them

1184
01:09:42.202 --> 01:09:45.562
accumulate under MPM conditions where you take the

1185
01:09:45.782 --> 01:09:49.052
nucleotides away. This is GAR, ICAR, and

1186
01:09:49.322 --> 01:09:53.202
DUMP. All of these, what they share in common is they're immediately

1187
01:09:53.213 --> 01:09:57.062
upstream of a folate-utilizing step, and to the extent we

1188
01:09:57.082 --> 01:10:00.942
can measure the downstream thing, so dTMP, it's depleted

1189
01:10:01.202 --> 01:10:04.922
under the MPM conditions. So this screamed to us that this

1190
01:10:05.002 --> 01:10:08.842
is probably related to folates. It turns out, well, what

1191
01:10:08.882 --> 01:10:12.862
are folates? Well, it turns out we grow cells in RPMI in 2.2

1192
01:10:12.982 --> 01:10:16.702
micromolar folates. We had measured, this is actually probably

1193
01:10:16.722 --> 01:10:19.662
super physiological. We can talk about that in a minute, but we had formulated this

1194
01:10:19.742 --> 01:10:21.962
originally with 115 nanomolar folates.

1195
01:10:22.422 --> 01:10:26.042
But regardless, if I simply take the folate level in

1196
01:10:26.122 --> 01:10:29.902
MPM and make it look like RPMI, now they don't care about

1197
01:10:30.242 --> 01:10:34.022
nucleotide salvage at all. So folates are driving this

1198
01:10:34.082 --> 01:10:37.382
phenotype. And in fact, this here is the

1199
01:10:37.402 --> 01:10:40.762
physiological range of folates, at least the one that's published in mice.

1200
01:10:41.132 --> 01:10:43.942
If you titrate, and this is RPMI is way up here.

1201
01:10:44.322 --> 01:10:48.022
If you titrate over this range, you can actually determine how fast cells

1202
01:10:48.062 --> 01:10:51.142
grow simply by the folates you provide them in the media.

1203
01:10:51.632 --> 01:10:55.402
And for those folate aficionados out there, it does matter if you use

1204
01:10:55.442 --> 01:10:58.002
folic acid or if you use things like 5-methyl

1205
01:10:58.962 --> 01:11:02.202
THF. Happy to talk about that if people are interested.

1206
01:11:03.382 --> 01:11:06.482
It shifts the curve slightly, but the finding is almost

1207
01:11:06.542 --> 01:11:09.582
identical. Now, why do I point this out?

1208
01:11:09.602 --> 01:11:13.442
Is because we tend to think of what's in culture as physiological, but it's

1209
01:11:13.482 --> 01:11:17.011
not. This is physiology. Physiology is

1210
01:11:17.042 --> 01:11:20.802
folate depletion. It turns out that standard mouse

1211
01:11:20.842 --> 01:11:23.551
chow is actually high in folates because we breed the mice.

1212
01:11:23.962 --> 01:11:27.861
But regardless, the standard folate in human blood, this is Rayann, who did the

1213
01:11:27.942 --> 01:11:30.672
work, her folate concentration is 31 nanomolar.

1214
01:11:30.702 --> 01:11:33.622
So we're actually overestimating in some of what we're doing there.

1215
01:11:34.022 --> 01:11:37.562
And I will point out that this actually matters because if we actually manipulate

1216
01:11:37.642 --> 01:11:41.302
folate levels in the mouse, we can actually control how fast the B-ALL grows,

1217
01:11:41.642 --> 01:11:45.152
particularly if we get rid of salvage and also affect survival of the mouse,

1218
01:11:45.702 --> 01:11:49.472
which I think this was important to us because I think it really pointed out that

1219
01:11:49.562 --> 01:11:53.522
us studying nucleotide metabolism is we're missing

1220
01:11:53.582 --> 01:11:56.542
something here important because it's far more constrained than normal.

1221
01:11:56.602 --> 01:12:00.022
It may explain, Gertha did a beautiful study where she actually looked and saw

1222
01:12:00.082 --> 01:12:03.942
folate salvage across many, many tissues in vivo, and I think this is actually

1223
01:12:03.982 --> 01:12:06.702
part of maybe that phenotype.

1224
01:12:07.642 --> 01:12:11.122
And then why does this actually matter for progression?

1225
01:12:11.162 --> 01:12:14.362
Well, the reason it matters for progression, we think, is as follows, and that is

1226
01:12:14.402 --> 01:12:18.282
that if you actually have issues with your nucleotides, it actually

1227
01:12:18.362 --> 01:12:20.322
rarely matters for RNA-based things.

1228
01:12:20.362 --> 01:12:24.022
It largely matters for DNA things, for DNA synthesis leading to

1229
01:12:24.062 --> 01:12:27.962
replication stress. And it turns out what actually happens, why the cells

1230
01:12:27.982 --> 01:12:31.402
grow slower in those conditions is because they experience DNA

1231
01:12:31.462 --> 01:12:35.282
replication stress. And this DNA replication stress from work from Peggy

1232
01:12:35.362 --> 01:12:39.002
Sue and Brian Doe, that again, is published, I don't have time to go into it, is

1233
01:12:39.062 --> 01:12:42.502
sufficient to be able to change gene expression state in cells,

1234
01:12:42.922 --> 01:12:46.172
which I think is actually interesting because I think what this says is that many

1235
01:12:46.262 --> 01:12:49.892
cells in our body, because they actually are in this situation where

1236
01:12:50.262 --> 01:12:54.202
they are constrained for synthesis, if they're in environments

1237
01:12:54.222 --> 01:12:58.122
where salvage is not perfect, they can now get this situation that might drive

1238
01:12:58.162 --> 01:13:01.542
gene expression changes, which of course is interesting in thinking about a

1239
01:13:01.562 --> 01:13:05.402
developmental mechanism, but it's also interesting in thinking about this

1240
01:13:05.482 --> 01:13:09.302
as sort of how could you get changes in gene expression related to cancer

1241
01:13:09.322 --> 01:13:13.183
biology.All right. Now in the remaining time, I want

1242
01:13:13.214 --> 01:13:16.334
to switch gears a bit and talk about whole body metabolism.

1243
01:13:16.374 --> 01:13:20.194
And this is really a phenotype that we've been interested in a

1244
01:13:20.234 --> 01:13:23.674
very long time, which is this notion that in pancreas cancer,

1245
01:13:24.154 --> 01:13:26.853
tissue wasting starts actually very, very early.

1246
01:13:27.274 --> 01:13:30.914
This is work we did with Brian Wolpin's lab, where basically they used a

1247
01:13:30.934 --> 01:13:34.904
variety of methods that even before patients are diagnosed, even with

1248
01:13:34.934 --> 01:13:37.984
non-metastatic cancer, they show evidence of muscle wasting.

1249
01:13:38.404 --> 01:13:42.154
And I'll point out this actually correlates with new onset diabetes, the muscle

1250
01:13:42.214 --> 01:13:45.974
wasting that is seen. And we've been interested in trying to figure this out, and

1251
01:13:46.014 --> 01:13:49.674
we've been trying to figure it out largely by using transplant models, which not

1252
01:13:49.754 --> 01:13:53.374
everyone in the field loves. But I will tell you, if you grow a tumor in the

1253
01:13:53.414 --> 01:13:56.824
pancreas, as the tumor grows, you end up getting

1254
01:13:56.854 --> 01:14:00.754
wasting of muscle and fat. Now, Yedij Goltekan, a

1255
01:14:00.774 --> 01:14:04.694
current postdoc in the lab, has been trying to sort out what's actually going on

1256
01:14:04.734 --> 01:14:08.334
with this phenotype, and I think largely

1257
01:14:08.414 --> 01:14:12.194
what he finds is also what Laura Deny, a former postdoc in the

1258
01:14:12.234 --> 01:14:16.174
lab, found and published back in 2018, is that what correlates

1259
01:14:16.214 --> 01:14:19.804
with this early tissue wasting with pancreatic tumor growth is

1260
01:14:19.894 --> 01:14:23.134
actually loss of normal pancreatic exocrine function.

1261
01:14:23.214 --> 01:14:26.914
Now, back when we published this paper, we said it was only about fat.

1262
01:14:26.974 --> 01:14:28.934
It turns out that's because we were using,

1263
01:14:29.954 --> 01:14:33.394
basically pancreatic enzyme replacement that was bought off of Amazon.

1264
01:14:34.214 --> 01:14:38.114
So when we use pharmaceutical-grade Amazon replacement, well, now we can fix

1265
01:14:38.194 --> 01:14:41.694
the muscle wasting. So I think it's really something about the

1266
01:14:42.574 --> 01:14:46.494
pancreas tumor causing exocrine insufficiency that is at

1267
01:14:46.574 --> 01:14:49.174
least driving the early tissue wasting in the mouse.

1268
01:14:49.814 --> 01:14:53.014
Now, many people discount this data because they say, well, this is not a good

1269
01:14:53.074 --> 01:14:57.064
model of pancreas cancer. And part of why they say that is the following, and

1270
01:14:57.094 --> 01:14:58.934
that's because I alluded to this earlier.

1271
01:14:59.014 --> 01:15:01.834
Humans with pancreas cancer get diabetes and mice don't.

1272
01:15:02.334 --> 01:15:06.214
In fact, mice are hypoglycemic at the time when they

1273
01:15:06.234 --> 01:15:08.594
lose the muscle and fat. Now, this makes sense.

1274
01:15:08.634 --> 01:15:11.914
If you're not digesting your food, you're going to be energy deficient.

1275
01:15:11.974 --> 01:15:15.264
You're going to be hypoglycemic. And if we give them exocrine replacement, we can

1276
01:15:15.314 --> 01:15:18.134
fix the blood glucose. So that actually sort of supports that.

1277
01:15:19.054 --> 01:15:22.794
Well, Yedij actually did an experiment to formally show that this

1278
01:15:22.834 --> 01:15:26.154
was the case, and it actually provided a really interesting clue that I think

1279
01:15:26.174 --> 01:15:28.634
explains the difference between mouse and humans.

1280
01:15:29.214 --> 01:15:32.774
This is a cool isotope tracing experiment that he did where effectively

1281
01:15:33.214 --> 01:15:37.194
he gave mouse a bolus of glucose or a bolus

1282
01:15:37.254 --> 01:15:41.004
of labeled glucose in starch and then looked at absorption and

1283
01:15:41.034 --> 01:15:44.974
disposal. So you'll see if I give labeled starch, the mouse with

1284
01:15:45.014 --> 01:15:48.474
pancreas cancer, because it doesn't have exocrine function or reduced exocrine

1285
01:15:48.514 --> 01:15:50.554
function, doesn't break down the glucose.

1286
01:15:50.594 --> 01:15:53.094
So you see less of a glucose spike and it's cleared.

1287
01:15:53.674 --> 01:15:56.854
But if you give a free glucose bolus, well, you actually see the same spike you see

1288
01:15:56.874 --> 01:16:00.814
in the control animals, and you also see that the area under the curve

1289
01:16:00.854 --> 01:16:04.354
is greater, which is consistent with reduced insulin function, which is

1290
01:16:04.394 --> 01:16:07.134
exactly the diabetes that you see in pancreas cancer.

1291
01:16:07.714 --> 01:16:10.734
And so we think there is reduced pancreatic

1292
01:16:11.174 --> 01:16:15.154
normal endocrine function that's happening in both mouse and humans.

1293
01:16:15.174 --> 01:16:16.874
And there's even evidence for this here.

1294
01:16:16.914 --> 01:16:20.134
Yes, insulin is low because the mice cannot digest their food.

1295
01:16:20.574 --> 01:16:24.514
But glucagon is also low, even though the mice are hypoglycemic, which

1296
01:16:24.554 --> 01:16:27.254
is also another sign of endocrine dysfunction.

1297
01:16:28.094 --> 01:16:31.994
Now, this is interesting because this is a dietary difference between mice and

1298
01:16:32.034 --> 01:16:32.514
humans.

1299
01:16:33.494 --> 01:16:37.454
You as humans, I don't care how good you are, unless you're Lou or Josh, who eats

1300
01:16:37.514 --> 01:16:38.724
only a ketogenic diet,

1301
01:16:39.774 --> 01:16:43.734
you eat free glucose. But the mice eat what we feed them, and there is

1302
01:16:43.814 --> 01:16:45.854
almost no free glucose in mouse chow.

1303
01:16:46.174 --> 01:16:49.414
We give mice a diet that is largely starch.

1304
01:16:49.654 --> 01:16:53.384
That's what it is. If we simply add free glucose to the

1305
01:16:53.434 --> 01:16:57.174
mouse chow, well, look at what happens. We now get elevation in blood glucose.

1306
01:16:57.234 --> 01:16:58.714
You get it in a wild-type mouse as well.

1307
01:16:59.134 --> 01:17:00.834
But it happens in the mice with pancreas cancer.

1308
01:17:00.863 --> 01:17:03.934
It does nothing to the muscle wasting, but it actually prevents the fat wasting,

1309
01:17:04.594 --> 01:17:06.794
which actually is the pattern that you see in humans.

1310
01:17:06.894 --> 01:17:10.824
So we think what the difference between humans and mice is is that humans have

1311
01:17:10.854 --> 01:17:12.324
exocrine and endocrine dysfunction.

1312
01:17:12.834 --> 01:17:16.254
But because they're eating free glucose, they actually have less fat wasting, more

1313
01:17:16.314 --> 01:17:18.614
muscle wasting, because this doesn't do anything to muscle wasting.

1314
01:17:19.583 --> 01:17:23.184
And they end up, in some cases, being hyperglycemic.

1315
01:17:23.264 --> 01:17:27.014
But not all human patients are hyperglycemic because it's probably dietary

1316
01:17:27.054 --> 01:17:31.034
dependent. We can do the exact same experiment

1317
01:17:31.074 --> 01:17:34.814
to prove that protein digestion is also affected. I won't take you through it.

1318
01:17:34.854 --> 01:17:38.714
It's basically the same result I showed you earlier, except using labeled

1319
01:17:39.154 --> 01:17:41.174
protein as protein or as free amino acids.

1320
01:17:41.544 --> 01:17:44.654
And if we simply give mice free amino acids, well, now we can fix the muscle

1321
01:17:44.714 --> 01:17:48.254
wasting. But it does absolutely nothing to the fat wasting, which actually is

1322
01:17:48.314 --> 01:17:52.004
further evidence that it's this normal pancreatic dysfunction that's

1323
01:17:52.054 --> 01:17:55.644
ultimately leading, at least in the mouse models, to this early tissue wasting

1324
01:17:56.294 --> 01:17:59.714
and actually defines which compartment is actually affected.

1325
01:18:00.654 --> 01:18:04.644
Now, I don't have time to get into this because I have 17 seconds left, but

1326
01:18:04.714 --> 01:18:07.974
in the end, Yedij wanted to ask, does this actually matter?

1327
01:18:08.014 --> 01:18:11.254
It turns out if you block the fat wasting, so we can do that dietarily in other

1328
01:18:11.294 --> 01:18:14.414
ways, it actually doesn't really matter for survival, but blocking the muscle

1329
01:18:14.454 --> 01:18:18.314
wasting does. And the most effective way to block the muscle wasting, at least in

1330
01:18:18.354 --> 01:18:20.734
his hands, was to knock out autophagy in the muscle.

1331
01:18:20.814 --> 01:18:24.554
So this is an ATG7 knockout, which is actually pretty good at preventing the

1332
01:18:24.614 --> 01:18:28.294
muscle wasting and also extends survival of the

1333
01:18:28.334 --> 01:18:32.254
mouse. Now, I'm out of time, so I want to close there.

1334
01:18:32.314 --> 01:18:36.054
But I think ultimately what this is saying is that it's actually an

1335
01:18:36.094 --> 01:18:39.714
effect of the cancer on the host that's leading to this systemic

1336
01:18:39.754 --> 01:18:43.174
effect, at least in this disease early on.

1337
01:18:43.314 --> 01:18:47.174
And it's not, I don't think that the cancer is

1338
01:18:47.254 --> 01:18:50.994
specifically doing this. I think the cancer doing this, this effect on the host, if

1339
01:18:51.054 --> 01:18:54.404
anything, is probably restraining the growth of the cancer.

1340
01:18:54.414 --> 01:18:57.744
But we have to be careful if we're actually going to go in and try to fix this.

1341
01:18:57.794 --> 01:19:01.774
Because if you fix it dietarily, well, you might protect the muscle, but now you're

1342
01:19:01.834 --> 01:19:05.214
also going to give the nutrients that are needed to the cancer.

1343
01:19:05.254 --> 01:19:08.854
Whereas, I don't know, if it was a way to block muscle-specific tissue

1344
01:19:08.874 --> 01:19:10.384
wasting, that would be a great thing to do.

1345
01:19:10.454 --> 01:19:13.694
Although pharmacologically, I'm not quite sure how to do that.

1346
01:19:13.714 --> 01:19:16.054
But with that, I just want to close. I want to thank the people in my lab.

1347
01:19:16.094 --> 01:19:19.714
I want to thank our collaborators, our funding sources, particularly the

1348
01:19:19.814 --> 01:19:23.754
Stephenson Global Pancreatic Cancer Research Institute, who really made

1349
01:19:23.774 --> 01:19:26.994
it possible for us to do especially the work I presented later.

1350
01:19:27.384 --> 01:19:28.654
And I also want to give a shout-out.

1351
01:19:28.794 --> 01:19:32.234
I have five trainees who happen to be here at this meeting.

1352
01:19:32.354 --> 01:19:35.234
All of them have posters. Two of them are undergraduates.

1353
01:19:35.314 --> 01:19:39.054
So Dia and Cindy, I encourage you guys go to check out their

1354
01:19:39.094 --> 01:19:42.774
posters. None of them are going to talk about anything that I presented in my talk,

1355
01:19:42.814 --> 01:19:44.654
and they all do awesome work. All right.

1356
01:19:44.674 --> 01:19:45.174
Thank you guys so

1357
01:19:45.234 --> 01:19:53.144
much.Yeah.

1358
01:19:54.164 --> 01:19:57.204
Thank you for the talk. My name is Omid Hajiasani from Case Western Reserve.

1359
01:19:57.884 --> 01:20:01.584
My question is about the first set of data that you showed about different tissues.

1360
01:20:01.644 --> 01:20:05.004
They have markers of different nutrient available to them.

1361
01:20:05.104 --> 01:20:09.023
Usually when these experiments are done, either a chow diet similar to average

1362
01:20:09.064 --> 01:20:10.064
Western diet has been

1363
01:20:10.944 --> 01:20:14.484
administered. I was wondering if we change a diet going to high

1364
01:20:14.564 --> 01:20:15.684
protein, ketogenic,

1365
01:20:16.664 --> 01:20:18.744
are we going to see different markers?

1366
01:20:18.884 --> 01:20:22.363
Or are we going to see that these tissues pick up the new nutrient and convert them

1367
01:20:22.444 --> 01:20:23.244
to what they're used to?

1368
01:20:23.564 --> 01:20:25.064
Yeah, that's a really great question.

1369
01:20:26.104 --> 01:20:29.224
So we've done a little bit work, and so what I will tell you is that if you change

1370
01:20:29.244 --> 01:20:32.524
the diet, you will affect the nutrients available in tissues,

1371
01:20:33.164 --> 01:20:35.664
but it's not as simple as what you would say, right?

1372
01:20:35.864 --> 01:20:39.494
So if you take glucose out of the-- Normal physiology still works.

1373
01:20:39.564 --> 01:20:41.944
Some nutrients are buffered better than others.

1374
01:20:42.304 --> 01:20:46.104
On a principle component plot, it'll move, but I

1375
01:20:46.124 --> 01:20:49.444
think there still is a defined characteristic of each

1376
01:20:49.454 --> 01:20:52.504
tissue that is then modulated by diet.

1377
01:20:52.924 --> 01:20:56.404
Now, I think this is a really interesting thing, because if you think about, well,

1378
01:20:56.464 --> 01:21:00.124
what are the dietary things that might increase cancer risk or kick off something

1379
01:21:00.164 --> 01:21:03.264
happening? Do those small changes matter?

1380
01:21:03.464 --> 01:21:07.264
I think that, in my view, remains an open question, although

1381
01:21:07.304 --> 01:21:10.964
many many groups, I think, are interested in this as a possibility.

1382
01:21:12.064 --> 01:21:14.783
I find the idea attractive, but we'll see.

1383
01:21:15.444 --> 01:21:15.704
Thank you.

1384
01:21:16.384 --> 01:21:19.364
But you have to measure. The key thing is you have to measure, you can't...

1385
01:21:19.584 --> 01:21:23.164
Karen did beautiful work. You take serine and glycine out of the diet, serine goes

1386
01:21:23.204 --> 01:21:25.544
down, but not all nutrients will do that.

1387
01:21:28.704 --> 01:21:31.024
Congratulations. It's beautiful work.

1388
01:21:31.464 --> 01:21:34.824
So, I realize that Josh's work a lot similar to yours.

1389
01:21:34.884 --> 01:21:38.544
That regarding the ketone diet, I wonder if

1390
01:21:38.644 --> 01:21:42.264
you see the similar, like ketone diet affected folate

1391
01:21:42.624 --> 01:21:45.224
change in... And that's question one.

1392
01:21:45.544 --> 01:21:48.404
And in Josh's study, he showed that

1393
01:21:48.824 --> 01:21:52.804
ketogenic diet also sensitize

1394
01:21:52.844 --> 01:21:56.744
the cancer cells to gemcitabine. I wonder if your

1395
01:21:56.784 --> 01:21:58.863
folate deficient also kind of

1396
01:21:59.924 --> 01:22:03.044
sensitize tumor cells to the chemotherapy.

1397
01:22:03.124 --> 01:22:06.924
Yeah. Both good questions. So we've not tested

1398
01:22:06.984 --> 01:22:09.204
what ketogenic diet does to folate levels.

1399
01:22:09.644 --> 01:22:11.404
My prediction is it shouldn't affect them.

1400
01:22:11.504 --> 01:22:14.344
I can't think of how that would be the case, but without measuring it, it's

1401
01:22:14.384 --> 01:22:18.204
impossible to know. In terms of does low folate

1402
01:22:18.244 --> 01:22:21.884
sensitize you to gemcitabine? We didn't try that because gemcitabine's never used

1403
01:22:21.944 --> 01:22:25.754
as a therapy in B-ALL, but it is something

1404
01:22:25.844 --> 01:22:29.604
that has been on the list to try in other cancers like pancreas

1405
01:22:29.664 --> 01:22:33.544
cancer. But without doing the experiment, I can't really speak

1406
01:22:33.584 --> 01:22:37.464
to answer the question. I could sort of do hand-waving reasons why it might

1407
01:22:37.504 --> 01:22:41.164
and hand-wavy reasons why it doesn't, which means we should do the experiment.

1408
01:22:41.624 --> 01:22:41.904
Thank you.

1409
01:22:44.784 --> 01:22:45.844
Oh, yeah. Garreta.

1410
01:22:46.664 --> 01:22:50.373
Hi, Matt. Amazing talk. I was very curious about the folate and

1411
01:22:50.384 --> 01:22:54.364
the salvagable nucleotides, and I was wondering whether you have

1412
01:22:54.424 --> 01:22:54.764
looked,

1413
01:22:55.744 --> 01:22:59.364
whether maybe what the nucleotides are doing is maybe fixing the

1414
01:22:59.384 --> 01:23:02.814
redox issue. Folates are really at an interesting

1415
01:23:02.884 --> 01:23:06.184
intersection that would need more redox, like

1416
01:23:06.284 --> 01:23:10.164
NADPH or NADH, and I wonder if you've looked at that

1417
01:23:10.244 --> 01:23:11.104
or thought about it.

1418
01:23:11.224 --> 01:23:15.124
Yeah. We've certainly thought about it. I'm obsessed with redox like you are.

1419
01:23:16.544 --> 01:23:19.924
I think the one experiment that may speak to that is whether or not

1420
01:23:20.104 --> 01:23:22.884
5-methylTHF versus folic acid makes a difference.

1421
01:23:22.944 --> 01:23:25.824
So for those who don't know, 5-methylTHF has to be recaptured.

1422
01:23:25.844 --> 01:23:28.933
They're different oxidation states, so they have to be captured in different ways.

1423
01:23:28.964 --> 01:23:32.304
We actually don't see a difference between those two in terms of constraints.

1424
01:23:33.844 --> 01:23:36.424
Where you become depleted is slightly different.

1425
01:23:36.464 --> 01:23:40.084
It turns out cells take up 5-methylTHF slightly better than folic

1426
01:23:40.184 --> 01:23:40.584
acid.

